<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Begins International Conference on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday morning convened an international conference to
accelerate the deployment of troops and U.N. personnel to run the
war-torn Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to ask for money as well as personnel from
those attending the one-day meeting that includes 10 foreign
ministers among 16 nations, who are described as "friends of the
Secretary-General for Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
Present at the meeting are representatives from 18 countries.
Shen Guofang, China's acting permanent representative to the
United Nations, took part in the coming meeting as the senior
representative of Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan.
</P>
<P>
Attending the one-day meeting are the foreign ministers of
Belgium, Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Italy, the Netherlands,
Spain, Turkey and Britain and the United States. Other nations
represented, in addition to Ambassador Shen, will be Austria,
Canada, Denmark, Japan, Russia and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the European Union, which is in charge of
reconstruction in Kosovo, and the Organisation for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, responsible for institution building, as
well as the Organisation of the Islamic Conference have also been
invited to the four-hour meeting.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the U.N. headquarters early on Wednesday,
Annan told reporters, "As you know, we do have a major
responsibility in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"I think it is important to bring the ministers together to
discuss what our needs are, to try and accelerate the deployment,
particularly of the troops, and the money we need to get the job
done, and also to bring them up to date as to what the situation
is on the ground and how things are going," he said.
</P>
<P>
In turn the ministers are expected to ask why the U.N.
political presence in Kosovo is barely visible, although experts
on such missions say other organisations would do worse.
</P>
<P>
The most pressing need is for an international police force to
tackle crime that has flourished with the exit of Serbian police
and military forces and the return of more than 300,000 ethnic
Albanian refugees. Only a small U.N. contingent has arrived from
the international mission in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Police seconded to the United Nations are in shorter supply
than soldiers, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Tuesday. "There
are no police barracks on our front lawn."
</P>
<P>
So far some 18 countries have said they would send 900 police,
which should begin pouring into Kosovo every five days next month
at 150-200 in each contingent, Eckhard said. They come from
Austria, Bangladesh, Bulgaria, Canada, Denmark, Egypt, Italy,
Kenya, Lithuania, Malaysia, Nepal, Pakistan, Romania, Tanzania,
Turkey, Britain, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to announce who will be his special
representative or chief administrator for the entire operation,
now run temporarily by Sergio de Mello, the Brazilian U.N.
undersecretary-general for humanitarian affairs. He has said he
would choose a European, a senior U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
But a one more portfolio is added to the existing list: a
deputy special representative for the U.N. mission in Kosovo,
known as UNMIK. "The deputy is to coordinate the four pillars of
the U.N. mission," he said.
</P>
<P>
Both Britain and France are vying for the post and some U.N.
officials prefer Martti Ahtisaari, who however does not finish his
term as president of Finland for another six months.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, which has been getting
tents and supplies to returning Kosovo refugees, says it has only
$2.4 million left for the month of July. It estimated up to 45,000
houses are now uninhabitable.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission will carry out its mandate without undermining
the sovereignty and territorial integrity of the Federal Republic
of Yugoslavia, as stipulated by the June 10 Security Council
resolution, the senior official added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
