<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Resolutions Clarify Parameters on Cyprus: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council's two
resolutions on Cyprus, approved on Tuesday, have clarified the
parameters in which the search for a Cyprus settlement will be
conducted, Cyprus Foreign Minister Ioannis Kasoulides said on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
One of the resolutions (1250/1999) is on Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's good offices mission (1250/1999) and another
(1251/1999) on the extension for a further six month period of
the mandate of the U.N. Peacekeeping Force in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
While passing the resolutions, the Security Council called for
unconditional talks for a settlement in Cyprus by putting all
issues on the table. Meanwhile, it endorsed a statement by the G-8
(seven most industrialized nations plus Russia).
</P>
<P>
The security council also reiterated that a settlement on the
island must provide for the establishment of a bizonal, bicommunal
federation.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides told the press that the two sides of Cyprus should
exhibit good will to create necessary preconditions and wait for
the Secretary-General's invitation for talks.
</P>
<P>
Kasoulides also said he was disappointed that no mention was
made in resolution 1251 on the missing persons issue.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government has accused the Turkish side of failing
to implement an agreement between the two sides, which provides
for the exchange of information about locations of graves and
return of remains of people killed during the 1974 war.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored agreement was signed on July 31, 1997 by
Cyprus President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1619 Greek Cypriots and Greeks (including five
U.S. citizens), were listed by the Cyprus government as missing
persons in the 1974 war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
