<HEADLINE> Pakistan Seeks Malaysia's Support To End Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday expressed
the hope that Malaysia will use its influence on India to halt
military action and resolve the Kashmir border dispute amicably.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani prime minister's Special Envoy Mian Abdul Waheed
said his country believed Malaysia would urge India to exercise
restraint and seek a peaceful solution.
</P>
<P>
"We hope Malaysia can use its influence on India so that it
will enter into dialogue with Pakistan to address this issue," he
told a press conference at the Pakistani High Commission here.
</P>
<P>
"We want a third party intervention. There are no prospects for
bilateral talks with India to end the dispute. Pakistan's repeated
initiatives for a dialogue through bilateral means have not
received positive signs from India," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mian, who arrived here two days ago on a mission to garner
world support to help end the dispute, said he believed India
would eventually stop all military mobilization if the world
voiced its concern over the matter.
</P>
<P>
Mian said he would hand over a letter from Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif to his Malaysian counterpart Mahathir Mohamad before
leaving for Tokyo later on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to him, India's lukewarm response to the holding of
talks to end the dispute had resulted in the Pakistani government
sending special envoys to European Union countries, Africa, Latin
America and Asia to seek their support to help end the conflict.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan wants peace and we want a dialogue to end the
dispute," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The conflict has cost many Kashmiris their lives and many
others had to seek refuge in Pakistan territory," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
