<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Kosovo Is Not U.N. Trustee Territory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China said here Wednesday
that "Kosovo is part of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia (FRY),
and it is not the United Nations trustee territory," calling upon
the international community to respect the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as Shen Guofang, China's acting permanent
representative to the United Nations, took the floor at an
international conference on Kosovo as the senior representative of
Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council Resolution 1244, adopted on June 10,
stipulates that all nations respect the sovereignty and
territorial integrity of the FRY, Shen said, "This should be
carried out in action, rather than simply expressed by words."
</P>
<P>
The international community, when rendering humanitarian relief
and the post-war reconstruction in Kosovo, should fully solicit
viewpoints from the FRY Government and the FRY should be involved
in the process, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China always maintains that all ethnic groups are equal in any
multi-ethnic country, they should live in harmony and work for
common development," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We do not favor discrimination or persecution against any
ethnic group, nor do we favor any ethnic cleansing," he said, "At
the same time, we also oppose any attempt to use the ethnic
problem to split a country."
</P>
<P>
"The ethnic problems in a country should be properly solved
through correct policies by the government and people of the
country," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the international peacekeeping forces in Kosovo, known as
KFOR, Shen said, the multi-national forces have made some progress
in carrying out the Security Council resolution since they entered
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
"However, there exists many problems in this regard," he said.
"After FRY's full military withdrawal from Kosovo in accordance
with relevant agreement, the multi-national forces should have an
unshirkable duty to safeguard peace and security in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"But the situation in Kosovo is continuing to be worsened," he
said, "For example, non-Albanian residents in Kosovo are still
being driven away, intimidated or even killed."
</P>
<P>
"In some areas in Kosovo, the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA) has
taken nearly all public facilities and organs under its control,"
he said, "Such a grave violation of the Security Council
Resolution 1244 can be no longer tolerated."
</P>
<P>
"The multi-national forces should take a quick action to fully
disarm the KLA and other armed groups so as to create a peaceful
environment, restore the normal social order and ensure the
safety, security and dignity of all ethnic groups in Kosovo," he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the post-war reconstruction, Shen said, the relevant program
should be well-balanced, rather than discriminative.
</P>
<P>
"NATO's 79-day wanton bombing of Yugoslavia has caused a huge
loss and serious humanitarian crisis in Kosovo and other regions
of Yugoslavia, including the destruction of the system to supply
water and power," he said, "This gravely affected the normal life
of the Yugoslav people."
</P>
<P>
The international should not put Serbia, a Yugoslav republic,
outside its relief operation program, "this is unfair and
inhumane," he said.
</P>
<P>
Foreign ministers or senior representatives of 18 countries and
the European Union, the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe and the Organization of Islamic Conference took part in
the four-hour meeting, during which they discussed how to
accelerate the deployment of troops in the war-torn Yugoslav
province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
