<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak signed a coalition agreement Wednesday with the
powerful ultra-Orthodox Shas party, moving significantly closer to
his goal of forming a broad-base government.
</P>
<P>
"Shas signed the coalition agreement. This brings us to 69
seats in parliament so far, giving him a wide government," said
Barak's spokeswoman Merav Parsi-Tzadok.
</P>
<P>
Occupying 17 seats in the 120-member parliament, Shas' support
is instrumental for Barak's effort to revive the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The National Religious Party (NRP) and the left-wing Meretz
have also signed an agreement respectively with One Israel to join
the coalition government led by Barak.
</P>
<P>
The next few days will be crucial for Barak in his coalition
forming effort as he has to submit the cabinet list to the
acting Knesset (parliament) one week before July 9, the deadline
for his government formulation stipulated by the election law.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who won the May 17 prime ministerial election, has to
rally support from other smaller parties to form a broad-based
coalition government because his One Israel alliance got only 26
seats in the 120-seat Knesset. 
</P>
