<HEADLINE> French Bank Stocks Rose With Failure of Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The stock values of three major
French private banks, the Banque Nationale de Paris (BNP), the
Societe Generale (SG) and Paribas, rose on Wednesday at the Paris
stock exchange after an government intervention to arrange an
agreement between them failed.
</P>
<P>
The three banks have been engaged in a merger battle since the
BNP tried to buy up SG and Paribas in a hostile takeover bid
announced in March.
</P>
<P>
SG and Paribas, which had by then agreed to merge, rejected the
bid by BNP, which was the largest ever take-over bid in France's
financial history and the first of its kind in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
The French central bank, Banque de France, and the government
arranged talks over the past week between the BNP as one side, and
SG-Paribas the other, to seek a consensus solution and avoid a
greater battle at the stock market.
</P>
<P>
After the announcement of failure of the talks, BNP's share
rose by 2.68 percent to 80.60 euros (77 U.S. dollars), SG by 4.10
percent to 175.50 euros (168 U.S. dollars) and Paribas by 1.68
percent to 108.90 euros (104 U.S. dollars) by mid-day Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dealers at stock market apparently welcomed the collapse of
the government intervention, after they sold off many stocks of
the three banks over the past week, causing an estimated 6.5
billion euro (6.1 billion U.S. dollars) loss for the banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
