<HEADLINE> Italian GDP to Grow by 1.2 Percent This Year, Studies Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The growth of Italy's gross domestic
product (GDP) this year is not likely to exceed 1.2% to fit the
country into the bottom slot in Europe but Italy will rise to
equal French and German GDP growth by 2002, a Italian economic
study center said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In other forecasts, the economists in Prometeria, an economic
think tank in Italian central city of Bologna, said greater labor
market flexibility could lead to the creation of 121,000 new jobs
of which 91,000 will be wage-earners.
</P>
<P>
Increasing oil prices will begin having an impact on domestic
prices in the coming months to help take inflation, now hovering
at 1.4 percent annually, to an average of 1.6 percent for the full
year.
</P>
<P>
Prometeria said that beginning in 2000, Italy should begin
reaping the benefits of financial stability in the form of
increasing domestic demand and economic activities more in line
with the norm in the euro area and showing greater potential over
the medium term.
</P>
<P>
According to the study center, domestic demand is likely to
increase at below last year's rate, about 1.6 percent compared to
2.6 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
In their outlook taking them to the year 2002, these
forecasters said domestic demand will be the engine of growth in
the coming year to lead fixed capital investments made by
enterprise.
</P>
<P>
Business and industry could draw benefit from a brighter
profitability picture, low interest rates and fiscal breaks so,
the report reasoned, demand and investments should both show
growth similar to the trends in Italy's European Union partner
countries.
</P>
<P>
The cycle of expansion in the Italian economy could be
associated with a long and substantial expansion in jobs with the
tertiary sector showing the way up.
</P>
<P>
In the absence of troubles originating outside the country,
inflation will remain low because of the lack of tension on the
import side and at home.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the two-year period, the gap between Italy and
France and Germany on the other side will be fully closed,
Prometeia said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
