<HEADLINE> Slide in Credit Growth Puts Retail Recovery in Doubt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON June 30 (Xinhua) - Consumer borrowing in Britain slid to
its lowest level for more than four years in May, the Bank of
England said.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank's latest figures released Wednesday, net
consumer credit rose by just 609 million pounds in May, almost
half market forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Analysts gave warning that the weaker-than-expected lending
figures could mean lower retail sales over the summer and throw
doubt on the strength of the retail recovery.
</P>
<P>
Jeremy Hawkins of Bank of America said: "The data is soft
enough to raise a few doubts about the strength of the recovery in
retail sales and we continue to expect another cut in the base
rate over the next few months."
</P>
<P>
But some of economists said the underlying trend remained
strong and pointed to figures showing that mortgage borrowing was
still robust.
</P>
<P>
Mortgage lending rose 2.7bn pounds in May, a slightly smaller
increase than April's 3.1bn and March's 3.2bn. The number of new
approvals was almost unchanged at 96,000, compared with 100,000 in
April.  
</P>
