<HEADLINE> Italy Swears to Save Life of Ocalan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government will exert
"every possible form of pressure" to save the life of Kurdish
rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan, condemned to death by a Turkish
court Tuesday, Deputy Premier Sergio Mattarella told parliament
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The deputy premier said Italy had moved at the bilateral and
multilateral level over the last few weeks to warn Turkey that a
death sentence would represent "a serious obstacle" to Turkey's
ambitions to join the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government will now impress on Turkish authorities
the need for the Turkish parliament to be fully aware of the
"inevitable" consequences of its ratification of the penalty.
</P>
<P>
According to Mattarella, if the parliament votes against the
death penalty, the vote "would have a great value and would not
fail to ease the progress of that country towards EU membership.''
</P>
<P>
Italy will exert similar pressure on the Turkish head of state,
who has the last word on the matter if parliament fails to block
the sentence.
</P>
<P>
Mattarella noted that the European Union Tuesday called for the
death penalty to be commuted in Ocalan's case, saying his
execution would be prejudicial for Turkey's hopes of joining the
EU. 
</P>
