<HEADLINE> U.S., Canada Sign Treaty on Salmon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The United States and Canada
signed an agreement on Wednesday aimed at protecting and building
up dwindling Pacific salmon supplies.
</P>
<P>
The Pacific Salmon Treaty, agreed to after five years of tough
negotiations and years of disputes between U.S. and Canadian
fishermen, revises a 1985 agreement to rebuild wild salmon runs
and ensure that both sides get a fair share of the catch.
</P>
<P>
The Treaty was signed by U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Thomas
R. Pickering and Canadian Ambassador Raymond Chtien at the U.S.
State Department's Treaty Room.
</P>
<P>
The treaty establishes two regional funds managed by both
countries to improve fisheries management and enhance cross-border
scientific cooperation.
</P>
<P>
It calls for the U.S. to spend 140 million U.S. dollars to
restore salmon habitat and other measures to rebuild stocks.
</P>
<P>
The deal divides up salmon among the two countries' fishermen
only after ensuring that enough remain to reproduce healthy and
growing runs, especially of wild chinook, sockeye and coho salmon.
</P>
<P>
Some salmon runs are being listed as endangered or threatened
under the U.S. Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
The agreement has the effect of reducing Canada's catch of
chinook salmon bound for streams in Washington, Oregon and Idaho,
while giving Canada more of the Fraser River sockeye salmon that
have been harvested by Washington and Oregon fishermen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Receive 3.7 Billion Dollars in Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) announced on Wednesday that they
have agreed that Mozambique has met the requirements for receiving
close to 3.7 billion U.S. dollars in debt relief from its external
creditors under the Heavily Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC)
Initiative.
</P>
<P>
The total debt relief package is worth 1.7 billion dollars in
today's values. Debt relief under the HIPC Initiative is expressed
in net present value terms -- today's values -- which discounts
future debt service payments to the current year's values, using
current discount (interest) rates and exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
This is the largest debt relief operation organized by the
international community under the HIPC Initiative so far, and
raises the total relief granted under the HIPC Initiative to 5.5
billion dollars, or 2.7 billion dollars in today's values.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique is the fourth country to reach the completion point
under the HIPC Initiative, along with Uganda, Bolivia and Guyana.
</P>
<P>
The HIPC Initiative debt relief will reduce Mozambique's
external public debt by almost two-thirds from about 2.7 billion
dollars to 1 billion dollars in today's values, on top of debt
relief provided under traditional mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's external debt-service obligations will fall to an
annual average of 73 million dollars in 1999-2005, compared with
an average of 169 million dollars that would have been due in the
absence of HIPC Initiative relief, and the 104 million dollars
actually paid in 1998.
</P>
<P>
By 2001, debt service due would fall to 8 percent of exports
and 10 percent of government revenues, compared with 19 percent of
exports and 23 percent of revenues actually paid in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique remains one of the world's poorest countries, with
about 70 percent of its population living in poverty. Debt relief
is expected to help deepen the social benefits of good economic
management and will enable the government to sustain increases in
spending for social development, the World Bank said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
The HIPC Initiative entails coordinated action by the
international financial community, including multilateral
institutions, to reduce to sustainable levels the external debt
burden of heavily indebted poor countries that pursue IMF and
World Bank-supported adjustment and reform program, but for whom
traditional debt relief mechanisms are insufficient.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank's International Development Association (IDA)
will provide debt service relief to Mozambique equivalent to 975
million dollars, or 381 million dollars in today's values.
</P>
<P>
This debt reduction will be delivered mainly through the
purchase and cancellation by the HIPC Trust Fund of IDA credits,
resulting in debt service savings of 327 million dollars in
today's values. In addition, an IDA grant has been made to support
improved economic management which will provide debt service
savings of 54 million dollars in today's values.
</P>
<P>
The IMF assistance under the HIPC Initiative will take the form
of a grant deposited into an escrow account to be used to cover
part of the debt service falling due to the IMF. This assistance,
to be delivered over the life of outstanding obligations to the
IMF, will amount to about 125 million dollars in today's values.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique also is expected to benefit form the changes
proposed by the recent G-7 Cologne Summit to strengthen the HIPC
Initiative. Once agreement is reached on an enhanced HIPC
Initiative, additional HIPC Initiative assistance will be
considered for Mozambique, the World Bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Europe's Major Markets End Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Shares in Europe's main markets
finished firmer Wednesday aided by some strong performances by
pharmaceutical and bank issues ahead of the Federal Reserve's rate
decision.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index of leading shares inched up as the market
regained its stability after Tuesday's fall. The index closed up
11.4 points at 6318.5.
</P>
<P>
Pharmaceutical giant SmithKline Beecham and Glaxo accounted for
all of the FTSE 100's gains; Glaxo added 2.5 percent, while
SmithKline jumped 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the electronic Xetra Dax finished up 0.35 percent
or 18.99 points, at 5378.52 after a day of restrained activity
ahead of the Federal Reserve's rate decision.
</P>
<P>
Banking stocks led the advancers after Goldman Sachs raised its
earnings-per-share forecast for Dax component Deutsche Bank by
seven percent, Dresdner Bank by six percent and Commerzbank by
three percent.
</P>
<P>
In Paris the Cac 40 index was up 0.73 percent to 4536.61
points. The breakdown of talks among banks involved in a three-way
bidding battle drove up their share prices as investors banked on
hopes the banks would become ripe for takeover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate Committee Approves U.N. Envoy Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Foreign
Relations Committee Wednesday approved the long-delayed nomination
of Richard Holbrooke to be U.S. ambassador to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The nomination was approved by a voice vote. Chairman Jesse
Helms of the Committee said it was "the quickest vote" in the
history of the panel.
</P>
<P>
The vote sends the nomination to the Senate floor. Holbrooke
supporters hoped the Senate could vote on the nomination by week's
end so the long-vacant top U.S. job at the United Nations could be
filled.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, an investment banker, is a former assistant
secretary of state and ambassador to Germany. He has also served
as Clinton's special envoy on the Balkans, and was the "architect"
of the peace accord that ended the civil war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton announced his intention to nominate Holbrooke
in June 1998, but the nomination was held up for nine months while
the Justice and State Departments investigated ethics allegations.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Relations Committee then conducted its own
investigation into the allegations, and held three separate
confirmation hearings on Holbrooke.
</P>
<P>
The allegations focused on private-sector contacts Holbrooke
had and speaking fees he received after leaving the State
Department for the private sector in 1996. Holbrooke admitted no
wrong-doing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Coalition of Peace and Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 30 (Xinhua) - By sealing a deal with the
powerful ultra-religious party Shas, Israeli Prime Minister-elect
Ehud Barak has secured broad-based support for his strategic goals
of reviving the peace process and achieving internal unity.
</P>
<P>
Joined by Shas, Barak's emerging coalition has already enjoyed
a majority of 69 seats in the 120-member Knesset (Parliament). The
expected joining of two additional parties will finally give Barak
a majority of 77 seats, the widest parliamentary majority in
Israel in years.
</P>
<P>
The broad support is exactly what Barak needs in the light of
the enormous tasks he faces: reach a permanent peace with the
Palestinians, resume negotiations with Syria, pull Israeli troops
out of south Lebanon, and heal the internal rifts deepened in the
last decade.
</P>
<P>
The brilliant ex-army chief won a landslide in the prime
ministerial election on May 17, but the One Israel alliance led
by his Labor Party seized only 26 seats in the new Knesset, which
has a record number of 15 factions.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Barak has had to struggle in the last six
weeks to court various factions with diversified demands in
order to put together a workable coalition.
</P>
<P>
While he could have formed a narrow government of left
and center parties, Barak has tried to include the right-wing
Likud and the Shas, the second and the third largest parties
in the Knesset, in his coalition.
</P>
<P>
At the start of the coalition talks, Barak preferred the
Likud to Shas in his government. Most of the secular voters,
a majority of them supporting Barak in the election, did not
want to see Shas, a party they accuse of disrespecting the
rule of law, to sit together with their parties.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the secular Likud would help Barak to carry
out internal reforms he promised: restrict the religious-coercion
in individual and public life, draft religious students who enjoy
military exemption for the last 50 decades, and adopt an
institution to guide the relationship between religious affairs
and politics.
</P>
<P>
But it soon turned out that the right-wing Likud was not an
ideal partner for peace. It disputed with Barak's guidelines in
almost every significant field.
</P>
<P>
Barak has pledged to halt increasing Jewish settlements in
the West Bank, and make necessary territorial concession over
the Golan Heights, the Syria territory seized by Israel in the
1967 Middle East war, in order to reach a comprehensive peace
deal with Syria.
</P>
<P>
But the Likud wanted the Jewish settlement activities to
continue and opposed any compromise on the Golan.
</P>
<P>
Besides, after suffering a humiliating defeat in the
election, the Likud was thrown into shambles. While the internal
struggle for its leadership intensified, the internal gaps over
whether it should join the coalition also became unbridgeable.
</P>
<P>
So, when Barak appeared to abandon the Likud and turned
to Shas, many people said he has changed his priority, putting
the peace process ahead of internal reform.
</P>
<P>
Although a pillar of Netanyahu's right-wing government, Shas
is relatively moderate on the peace process. And, since its
spiritual leader makes the final say, Barak would get a
unanimous support of the party.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Barak wheeled and dealed patiently, insisting that
the convicted Shas leader Aryeh Deri have to resign, persuading
the left-wing Meretz party to retreat from its objection to
sitting in the government with Shas, and resisting criticisms
from the impatient media and members inside his One Israel who
called on him to quickly form a narrow but "workable" government.
</P>
<P>
While he almost used up the time allocated the law,
Barak's labors finally bear fruit.
</P>
<P>
Although it is true in saying that by choosing Shas rather
than the Likud, Barak has put the peace process on top of his
agenda, it is also true that it will be easier for him to achieve
his goal of unity by including Shas in his government.
</P>
<P>
Shas represents low-income Middle East Jews, who feel they
are discriminated in this country established by the "elite
class." It scored a stunning victory in the parliamentary
election, jumping from 10 seats to 17, just because its
supporters regarded the conviction of Deri as an oppression of
their whole class.
</P>
<P>
If Shas remains outside the government, which means its
schools and welfare networks will face financial difficulty, the
rift between its supporters and the country will only be
deepened.
</P>
<P>
In this sense, by including Shas in his government, Barak
will achieve, rather than delay or abandon, his goal of
internal unity. Many Israelis call the incoming government a
"coalition of peace," but observers say, actually, it is a
"coalition of peace and unity." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
