<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Launches War Against Malaria in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO), in conjunction with interested parties, has launched a
campaign against malaria in a bid to cut down the death rate and
boost the economy of Africa, an official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
WHO regional director for Africa Ebrahim Samba made these
remarks during a meeting dubbed Roll Back Malaria (RBM) in the
Zimbabwean capital.
</P>
<P>
Samba said there was guaranteed success of combating malaria
due to vastly improved knowledge and the availability of better
drugs for its control.
</P>
<P>
"Unlike previous anti-malaria efforts, RBM is an all embracing
 initiative which seeks to mobilize and coordinate a global
coalition including leaders from malaria-endemic countries, WHO,
United Nations agencies, non-governmental organizations,
scientific communities and private and public sector
organizations," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Roll Back Malaria partnership would pool resources
to eliminate costly overlaps.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting would review implementation of Roll Back
Malaria in Africa and how the partnership would work to support
the project.
</P>
<P>
More than one million Africans are estimated to be killed by
malaria each year.
</P>
<P>
Economic losses which are attributed to the disease in 1998
reached two billion U.S. dollars and were projected to reach three
billion U.S. dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
More than 150 participants from various countries including
Tanzania, Cote D'Ivoire, Mali, Sudan, Senegal and Ireland are
attending the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
