<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Discuss Ratification of International </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Southern African government
officials will meet in Pretoria next week to discuss ratification
of a statute providing for the creation of an international
criminal court, the South African Justice Department said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The statute, adopted by a United Nations diplomatic conference
in Rome last year, needs to be ratified by 60 countries before
such a court can be set up.
</P>
<P>
So far only one country, Senegal, has ratified the document.
</P>
<P>
Half of the 14 Southern African Development Community (SADC)
member states, including South Africa, have signed the statute,
which amounts to an approval of its text.
</P>
<P>
"While SADC states are favorably disposed to ratification at
the earliest opportunity, a number lack the legal expertise,
experience and resources to identify and draft the national
legislation necessary for compliance with the statute, with the
resultant delay in their early ratification," the department said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
It said the regional workshop, from Sunday to Friday next week,
would aim to familiarize government officials with the provisions
of the statute, and to discuss its implications for national
legislation.
</P>
<P>
It would also seek a coordinated approach to ratification, and
an agreement on a common negotiating strategy.
</P>
<P>
South African Justice and Constitutional Development Minister
Penuell Maduna will open the workshop Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strong Earnings Turnaround for Consolidated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Consolidated African Mines
(CAM) reported Wednesday a huge surge in earnings which took it
from a loss of 178.6 million rand (29.7 million U.S. dollars) for
the past nine months ending March 1998 to an attributable profit
of 132.5 million rand (22 million dollars) for the past financial
year.
</P>
<P>
CAM chief executive Brett Kebble said here in a statement that
the company's turnaround was the result of a vigorous clean-up of
its portfolio of interests since last year's unbundling of two
major gold mines -- Saflife and JCI Limited.
</P>
<P>
CAM and its major investment, JCI Gold, also announced they
were selling their non-gold assets to New Mining Corporation in a
273.4- million-rand (45.5 million dollars) deal designed to set
the scene for a proposed restructuring of their gold interests
involving Western Areas, Randfontein Estates, Randgold and
Exploration and Randgold Resources.
</P>
<P>
Kebble said the sale of the non-gold assets was a further step
in a process designed ultimately to lead to the creation of a new
world-class gold business.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition of the non-gold assets of CAM and JCI Gold was
sure to transform New Mining Corporation, a fledgling empowerment
group, and to significantly enhance its asset base and make it a
substantial player in the global diamond industry, the corporation
said.
</P>
<P>
New Mining Chairman Professor Wiseman Nkuhlu said the
acquisition of the assets would provide the company with
income-producing assets, a source of cash flow and substantial
mineral interests which could be developed either by New Mining
itself or through mergers and joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
"They will add critical mass to New Mining and provide it with
a solid platform for implementing its strategy of becoming a
substantial and diversified resources company," Nkuhlu said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
