<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Independent Counsel Ends Whitewater Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.S. independent counsel
Kenneth Starr Wednesday ended the investigation of President
Clinton and his wife Hillary Clinton into their financial dealings
in Arkansas with two fresh guilty pleas from key Whitewater figure
Webster Hubbell.
</P>
<P>
"After five years, it's over. Our lives can begin again,"
Hubbell said outside the courthouse after being sentenced to one
year of probation.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell pleaded guilty to misleading federal regulators to
cover up legal work he performed with Mrs. Clinton on a failed
Arkansas land development called Castle Grande.
</P>
<P>
He also pleaded guilty to a less serious misdemeanor violation
of failing to pay part of more than 890,000 dollars in owned taxes
and penalties.
</P>
<P>
U.S. District Judge James Robertson accepted Hubbell's guilty
pleas and agreed to a request from Starr's prosecutors not to
sentence the 51-year-old Hubbell to any more time in prison.
Robertson placed Hubbell on one year probation.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell, a longtime friend and associate of the Clintons,
previously served a 16-month prison sentence for bilking his law
firm and his clients.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell said President Clinton and first lady Hillary did
nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
"I told the office of independent counsel, as I told them
five years ago, that I had no knowledge of any wrongdoing on the
part of Mrs. Clinton or the president," he said.
</P>
<P>
Outside the courthouse, Starr said Hubbell's plea brought to an
end the Arkansas phase of his investigation. For five years, he
has been investigating the Clinton's investment in the failed
Whitewater real estate venture in the 1980s in Arkansas State.
</P>
<P>
Hubbell's plea deal prevented Mrs. Clinton from potentially
testifying as a prosecution witness at Hubbell's trial next month
as she prepares a possible campaign for a Senate seat from New
York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
