<HEADLINE> Feature: PLA Open Barracks Day Impresses HK Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The display of military skills
and weapons of the People's Liberation Army (PLA) stationed in the
Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) repeatedly won warm
applause from visitors to their barracks on the Open Barracks Day
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The formation drill and martial arts performance by the PLA
soldiers are quite wonderful and their morale and discipline
greatly impressed me," said Miss Miao, a bank clerk.
</P>
<P>
Miao, who came to visit the PLA barracks for the second time,
said the Open Barracks Day helps increase her understanding of the
People's Liberation Army and she now has more confidence in the
army.
</P>
<P>
The PLA Hong Kong garrison opened three barracks of the ground,
navy and air forces in Stanley, Stonecutter Island and Shek Kong
Thursday on the occasion of the second anniversary of the
establishment of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of local residents, old and young, went to visit the
barracks despite the scorching sun.
</P>
<P>
Besides demonstrating their military skills and weapons, the
PLA soldiers showed the visitors around their libraries,
recreation centers and dormitories. Singing and dancing
performances were also staged for the visitors, who were also
invited to join the soldiers in singing karaoke and playing chess.
</P>
<P>
The PLA troops first came to the Hong Kong SAR when China
resumed the exercise of sovereignty over the region on July 1,
1997. And many Hong Kong residents are curious about their work
and life here.
</P>
<P>
On the Open Barracks Day, people get a chance to see with their
own eyes the life of the soldiers and even get to learn of some of
their "privacies," Terry Tam, a high-school student said at the
PLA ground troops base in Stanley.
</P>
<P>
"The clean and tidy barracks and dormitory rooms of soldiers
reflect their spirit," said Tam, adding humorously that he is
happy now that he knows the secret of how PLA soldiers shape their
quilts like bean-cakes.
</P>
<P>
Feng Wei, a PLA spokesman, said the open barracks program,
which is the third since the PLA began to be stationed in Hong
Kong, serves as a main channel for the local residents to get to
know the army.
</P>
<P>
Local people have offered much support to the PLA troops in the
past two years and the PLA garrison often receives telephone calls
from local people inquiring about the troops' life and activities
here, he added.
</P>
<P>
Feng said visitors talk more freely to soldiers on this open
barracks day and the ties between the army and local people have
become closer.
</P>
<P>
At a calligraphy and painting exhibition room, a PLA soldier
gave his calligraphy work with the words "army and civilians are
the same family" to a lady, who visited the barracks together with
her children.
</P>
<P>
The lady, a Ms Li, said she would keep the calligraphy work as
a souvenir for her children and ask them to learn from the PLA its
devotion to the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
