<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal to Make SAARC More Action-Oriented: King </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- King Birendra told parliament
Thursday that Nepal shall make efforts to make the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) more action- and
result-oriented.
</P>
<P>
Outlining the government's policies and programs for the
1999/2000 fiscal year starting mid-July, King Birendra called for
full cooperation from all countrymen to make a success the 11th
SAARC summit to be held in November in Kathmandu.
</P>
<P>
SAARC was formed in December 1985 to promote economic and
social development in the region through cooperation among its
seven member states -- Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the Maldives,
Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Expressing Nepal's unflinching faith in the principles
enshrined in the United Nations Charter, King Birendra said his
country will continue to follow the non-aligned foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
He said the Nepali government will continue its diplomatic
efforts to solve peacefully the Bhutanese refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
About 100,000 Bhutanese refugees are staying in camps in
eastern Nepal after being forced to flee Bhutan in 1989 and the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali Congress government was formed on May 31. It is the
first majority government in the Himalayan kingdom in four and a
half years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
