<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Marks Joint Ventures Law Anniversary (part one) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A high profile symposium was held
here today to mark the 20th anniversary of the promulgation of the
Law on Chinese-Foreign Equity Joint Ventures.
</P>
<P>
 Tian Jiyun, vice-chairman of the National People's Congress (
NPC) Standing Committee, and State Councilor Wu Yi attended the
symposium, which was jointly hosted by the NPC and the Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
 On this day 20 years ago, the NPC, China's top legislative
body, approved and promulgated the law, the first of its kind to
focus on China's use of foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
 The implementation of the law represented the formal launch
of China's national policy of opening to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
 Following that, China drew up a series of laws and
regulations on the utilization of foreign capital. Now, a basic
legal system with Chinese characteristics has come into shape,
which has greatly boosted foreign investments in the country.
</P>
<P>
 Since the first Sino-foreign joint venture was set up in
China in 1980, a total of 324,700 such ventures have been approved
in the country, involving actual investment of 267.45 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
 Official statistics showed that since 1993, China has ranked
first among developing countries in attracting foreign capitals.
</P>
<P>
 Statistics also showed that in 1998, China's industrial
enterprises with overseas investments turned out of 1,416.25
billion yuan (about 170 billion U.S. dollars) worth of goods,
which accounted for 24 percent of the country's total industrial
output.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spokesman on EU's New Decision on China's Wooden Crates (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The EU's June 1 announcement urged member nations to adopt
immediate measures to implement new inspection standards for
packaging using wooden crates or materials for exports from China
after June 10.
</P>
<P>
Gao Hucheng, MOFTEC assistant minister, met with the European
Union Ambassador to China Endymion Wilkinson on June 11 to lodge a
serious complaint about the EU's decision, saying that China
reserves the right to take further actions.
</P>
<P>
But, MOFTEC officials told Xinhua on June 18 that Chinese
export companies have been told to improve the quality and
standard when using wooden boxes for packing their export products
in a special notice issued by MOFTEC and several other Chinese
ministerial departments.
</P>
<P>
Export companies have been warned to carefully select wooden
boxes, crates and pallets according to the new required standards.
Below standard wood must be specially treated before being used as
packaging for exports.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that the EU side will, in accordance with the spirit
of bilateral agreement on trade and economic cooperation, enhance
negotiations and avoid unilateral trade restriction measures that
will affect adversely the normal growth of bilateral trade," Hu
said today.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said that China also hopes that the EU and its
member nations would reduce arbitrary actions in carrying out
relevant regulations so as to maintain normal development of
bilateral trade relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
