<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Looks for Buyers of State Telecom Company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is looking for
potential buyers worldwide of the state-owned Tanzania
Telecommunications Company Limited (TTCL), local media reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Privatization with new investment capital, technology and
management will enable the TTCL to provide its customers with
better telephone services, a senior official was quoted as saying
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We expect considerable interest from investors," said John
Rubambe, Executive Chairman of the Parastatal Sector Reform
Commission (PSRC).
</P>
<P>
"There is superb potential for a private telecom company in
Tanzania and TTCL will become that company."
</P>
<P>
The TTCL currently has only 127,000 lines connecting its
customers countrywide that can offer telephone services to about
two percent of Tanzanian families.
</P>
<P>
Rubambe said that advertisements for prospective buyers have
been placed in local, regional and international publications for
bidders.
</P>
<P>
Up to 14 percent of shares will be sold to international
financial organizations, 10 percent to Tanzania financial
organizations and five percent to TTCL employees, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The winning bidder will receive 35 per cent of TTCL shares and
has management control of the company under government
regulations," Rubambe said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, TTCL received Wednesday a license from the Tanzania
Communications Commission (TCC) to provide its mobile cellular
phone service.
</P>
<P>
Operated under a subsidiary company called Celnet Mobile (TZ)
Ltd, the service will be digital with a countrywide coverage
backed by TTCL's own modern network.
</P>
<P>
TTCL expects the service will be of very high quality and be
offered at easy, affordable tariffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
