<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Surge on U.S. Interest Rate Outlook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian sharemarket kicked
off the new financial year with a more than a 1-percent surge on
Thursday, buoyed by positive news on the outlook of U.S. interest
rates.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index stacked on 33.2 points, or
1.12 percent, to 3,002.1 points.
</P>
<P>
But it closed well down from its peak of 3,025 points after a
bout of afternoon profit-taking, Morgan Stockbroking adviser Simon
Reed said.
</P>
<P>
"The market moved aggressively higher today following on from
the positive lead from Wall Street overnight," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index Thursday surged 37.8 points to
5,225.9, while the all resources index raced 37.6 points higher,
or 3.11 percent, to 1,247.4 points, encouraged by an overnight
rally in copper prices.
</P>
<P>
Industrials were also up across the board, with media and
banking stocks among the better performers.
</P>
<P>
The banking index gained 26.1 points to reach 6,529.8, with ANZ
being the biggest mover, soaring 23.1 cents to 11.34 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank hit a high of 25.75 Australian
dollars before being pegged back by profit taking to end 5 cents
firmer for the day at 25.05 Australian dollars while Westpac rose
3 cents to 9.83 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Commonwealth Bank shed 2 cents to 24.03 Australian dollars
after hitting a peak of 24.7 Australian dollars in earlier trade.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 599.84 million shares traded for 1.52
billion Australian dollars (1 billion U.S. dollars). Rising stocks
outnumbered falling ones 832 to 486 while 365 stocks remained
steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
