<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Issue Bonds to Stabilize Local Currency Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The South Korean government Thursday
decided to issue South Korean won-denominated bonds worth up to
five trillion won (some 4.17 billion U.S. Dollars) to stabilize
local currency market.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made at a ministerial meeting Thursday to
check the won's recent appreciation against the greenback produced
by the current-account surplus and inflows of stock funds from
abroad and a reduction in export competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Ministry of Finance and Economy said the move
will contribute greatly to stabilizing foreign exchange rates once
the treasury bonds with maturity less than 10 years are issued.
</P>
<P>
The stabilization bonds will result in a rise in won-based
debts as well as in foreign exchange holdings, the two effects
offsetting each other with adverse effects minimized, said the
ministry.
</P>
<P>
Thursday, the South Korean won was traded at 1,158.50 U.S.
dollar at the foreign exchange market here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
