<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Disney Park Negotiations Extended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The negotiations concerning the
construction of a Disney Theme Park in Hong Kong have produced "
significant progress" but no agreement has been reached yet and
talks were extended by four months.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's Secretary for Economic Services Stephen Ip told a
press conference Thursday that "significant progress" has been
made over the past four months in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Financial Secretary Donald Tsang announced in his Budget Speech
on March 3 that the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
government and the Walt Disney Company had agreed to engage in
intensive negotiations with a view to determining, by June 30,
whether a Disney project could be brought to fruition in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Ip said the Disney project is highly complex and requires a
thorough analysis of the economic costs and benefits and careful
evaluation of the technical and financial issues.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, "we need a further period of serious
discussions to make sure that the terms of any agreement on a
Disney project are mutually acceptable and can be reached in
sufficient detail for both sides to be comfortable."
</P>
<P>
What is important is that "we have made significant progress"
in the past four months and "we are continuing our negotiations
with a view of reaching an agreement by the end of October," Ip
said.
</P>
<P>
Also present at the press conference, Commissioner for Tourism
Mike Rowse said both sides in the negotiations are satisfied with
the "considerable progress" made and there is not anything "
holding it up" but some technical details involving such aspects
as transport and reclamation remain and require further
discussions.
</P>
<P>
He insisted that the Disney project is a "useful asset" for
Hong Kong's tourism sector, so the SAR side does not want to "lose
momentum" in the negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
