<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 07:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Banks Urged to Aid Small Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Banks in Lebanon were urged to
extend soft loans to small businesses in a bid to stimulate
investments and create more jobs, the Daily Star reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It has been proven that banks extending modest loans to small
investors will have a good turnover," said Youssef Khalil, head of
the financial operating department at the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a seminar Wednesday on the mechanism to create
liquidity in the local market, Khalil said that recent statistics
show that small businesses usually settle their commitments to the
banks faster than big borrowers.
</P>
<P>
He said Lebanese farmers get 1.5 percent of the total bank
loans, while industries receive under 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, many small farmers are forced to go to loan
sharks to get loans with staggering interest rates that sometimes
reaches more than 200 percent."
</P>
<P>
According to the Central Bank's statistics, less than 1
percent of borrowers receive 49 percent of the total bank loans,
while 47 percent of borrowers account for only 2.3 percent of
the money lent.
</P>
<P>
Banks have extended loans worth some 12 billion U.S. dollars to
the private sector since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Fahim Mo'dad, vice governor of the Central Bank, said that
Lebanon did not have a cash flow problem.
</P>
<P>
"Banks are liquid and can help activate the economy with their
loan programs," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Central Bank may consider amending the
existing money and credit law to allow Islamic banks to operate
in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
At the seminar, the Central Bank was also called on to allow
Islamic banks to operate in Lebanon because they have huge liquidity.
</P>
<P>
Mo'dad said the Central Bank, in collaboration with the
Association of Banks in Lebanon, would soon create a loan
guarantee fund to extend soft loans to small-and-medium-size
businesses which would benefit about 13,000 small institutions.
</P>
<P>
"This program will create 56,000 job opportunities and also
increase the economy growth by 2 to 3 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mo'dad estimated that 3 billion dollars in commercial banks
were not being properly used to stimulate investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
