<HEADLINE> Mozambican President Happy with Debt Relief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Jaoquim
Chissano expressed satisfaction and gratitude to international
institutions, including the World Bank, for the partial debt
relief, saying that this is an important step for total debt
relief.
</P>
<P>
Chissano made the remark Wednesday in Namacurra Town of
northwestern Mozambique's Zambezia Province, where he is on a work
tour, the Noticias daily reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The debt relief is an indication that Mozambique's economic and
 political reforms are being recognized, Chissano said.
</P>
<P>
He said that debt relief allows the government to use more
money on the development of basic infrastructure and education,
which serve as the basis for high-speed and sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
While expressing his thanks to creditor countries and
organizations, like the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund, CHissano said that the timely donations by them have
contributed to the success of reform in the country.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that the World Bank and the International
Monetary Fund decided Wednesday to write off mozambique's 3.7
billion U.S. dollars debt.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has a total debt of about 5.7 billion dollars,
mostly borrowed during the 16-year-long civil war.  
</P>
