<HEADLINE> Philippines Confident of Rice Self-Sufficiency by 2001 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
has vowed to help modernize the agricultural sector so that the
nation could be self-sufficient in rice, corn and sugar by the
year 2001, a presidential news release said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on a regular TV program, Estrada said governors
nationwide have pledged to help his administration attain this
goal.
</P>
<P>
He said food security and agricultural modernization are the
potent tools that would aid his administration in wiping out
poverty in the country and providing adequate food for each
Filipino.
</P>
<P>
The president also voiced his confidence in this sector, citing
a 31-percent growth in rice production and a 62-percent growth in
corn harvest during the first three months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to a study, however, the barriers to the development
of agriculture in the nation include the lack of irrigation
systems, post-harvest facilities and other infrastructure in the
countryside.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said that at present the annual average rice
import of the country is 600,000 tons. 
</P>
