<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Defending Champions Norway Advance into Semifinals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SAN JOSE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Defending champions Norway beat
Sweden 3-1 to set up a semifinal clash with China in the 3rd women's
World Cup soccer tournament here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The defending champions met a stiff resistence from the Swedish
team in the first half. Though they dominated the pace of the match
with their long ball tactics, they could not find the right way to
tear off the Swedish team's defence line.
</P>
<P>
After the goalless first half, Norway enjoyed greater advantage
both physically and tactically. At the 51st minute, they were
awarded a free-kick and Ann Kristin Aarones headed home the
perfectly positioned cross to give her team a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
The Swedish team became more nervous after conceding the goal.
Seven minutes later, Marianne Pettersen, who was named the best player
of the match, broke down the right flank and volleyed a cross over the
head of the Swedish goal-keeper Ulrika Karlsson straight into the net.
</P>
<P>
Norway's third goal came at the 71th minute when Karlsson
brought down Pettersen in the area. Hege Riise converted the
penalty kick to put Norway 3-0 ahead.
</P>
<P>
The defending champions played relaxed and as the game headed
into the injury time they lost their concentration for a while.
That was enough for the Swedish team to score a consolation goal at
the first minute of the injury time.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in a match between China and Russia, the Chinese team
proved they are deserved the status of being one of the favorites of the
tournament by scoring a comfortable 2-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
By entering the semifinals, China and Norway qualify for the
2000 Sydney Olympic Games. Australia earn an automatic ticket to
the Olympics as the host team. While Russia and Sweden still have
their chances of qualifying.
</P>
<P>
According to the qualifying regulations set by FIFA, only the team
from the four losing quarterfinals which has the worst group
competition results will miss the Olympic Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
