<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Training Director Back to Coaching Badminton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Badminton Association of
Indonesia (PBSI) official in charge of athletes' development M.F.
Siregar denied rumors which said national training director
Christian Hadinata would resign from his post.
</P>
<P>
"It's not true. Christian will just focus his attention on
coaching the men's doubles because it's the only event we have a
chance to win a gold in the 2000 Olympics," Siregar was quoted by
The Jakarta Post Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that Christian would resign due to disappointment
over PBSI chairman Subagyo Hadisiswoyo, who often used his veto
rights to disapprove of Christian's training programs.
</P>
<P>
But Christian himself said he wanted to only focus on the men's
doubles training.
</P>
<P>
Siregar said Christian would be replaced either by himself or
deputy Hadi Nasri until the Olympics 2000.
</P>
<P>
"Can you imagine if we fail to win a gold in the Olympics," he
said, referring to Indonesia's shameful failure in the Sudirman
Cup and World Championships in Copenhagen where none of the
national shuttlers reached the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
Christian, a former doubles specialist, had contributed a great
deal to the 1996 Olympics gold when his athletes Ricky Subagja and
Rexy Mainaky beat Malaysians Cheah Soon Kit and Yap Kim Hock in a
thrilling deciding game final.
</P>
<P>
He also teamed up with Candra Wijaya and Sigit Budiarto who
beat the same Malaysian pairs of Cheah and Yap in the 1997 World
Championships.
</P>
<P>
Christian said his position as training director made it
difficult to make a decision on the men's doubles because other
coaches from other events would consider him subjective.
</P>
<P>
But Herry Imam Pierngadi and Sigit Pamungkas have been coaching
the men's doubles since Christian was appointed director in
December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Siregar said PBSI could not rely on Herry due to his lack of
experience.
</P>
<P>
"We used to have Atiek (Djauhari) who was also experienced to
help Christian. But Herry was too young to prepare athletes for
the biggest event," he said.
</P>
<P>
Atiek resigned from PBSI last year and moved to Malmo, Sweden,
where he is responsible for the Swedish national team.
</P>
<P>
Siregar said Christian had to make his priorities on which
doubles team to concentrate on to qualify for the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
"We already have the 1999 All England champion Candra Wijaya
and Tony Gunawan and new partnerships of Flandy Limpele and Eng
Hian. But we are still looking for the third pair. We have the
1996 Olympics Ricky and Rexy and old hands Antonius and Denny
Kantono," he said.
</P>
<P>
Another pair preparing to qualify for the Olympics is Sigit
Budiarto and new partner Halim Heryanto. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Wang Picked by Dallas Mavericks in NBA Draft ( Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese center Wang Zhizhi has
been picked 36th in the second round of the National Basketball
Association draft by Dallas Mavericks on Wednesday to become the
first Asian basketball player in history ever to be drafted by an
NBA team.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is 2.12 meters tall and weighs 115 kilograms,
averaged 11.1 points and 5.6 rebounds for China at the Atlanta
Olympic Games in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who turns 22 on July 8, plays for China's five-time
national champion Bayi Rockets.
</P>
<P>
He led China's CBA league by blocking last season and was third
in scoring.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the Dallas Mavericks, I'm so glad that we will
have the chance to work with Wang Zhizhi because he's a young
basketball player with great talent," said Donn Nelson, head coach
of the Dallas Mavericks, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"His draft story will remind basketball fans of Toni Kukoc,
Dino Radja, Drazen Petrovic, Cedric Cegallos P.J. Brown,. and even
Dennis Rodman, all of whom succeeded after being drafted at the
same position as Wang," Nelson added.
</P>
<P>
As the first NBA coach ever visited China, Nelson spent nine
days in Beijing and Shanghai last summer and had basketball
clinics for Chinese Basketball Association (CBA) coaches, Junior
Team, Pro team, and young kids.
</P>
<P>
"Two things made me fall in love with this country, great
people and the love Chinese people give to the game," Nelson said.
"I found that the potential of basketball in China is huge; the
CBA has done a great job of making this game popular in China. The
game will become much more popular sport in the country with the
drafting of Wang into NBA."
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to see that China has produced the first Asian
basketball player to make the NBA," Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
But Nelson said the Mavericks will respect CBA's decision if
they do not allow Wang to play in NBA very soon.
</P>
<P>
He said: "I know it might be difficult for Wang to come out and
play in the NBA very soon since the Army Club might need him to
stay and carry the team for a couple of more years. The Mavericks
will respect the special situation of China basketball and Army
basketball."
</P>
<P>
Nelson added: "But the reason we drafted him is that Wang
deserves this pick because of his basketball skills and potential,
and I hope this young person will have the chance to make his hoop
dream come true soon.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't want to make the same mistake that the Golden State
Warriors made in 1990 when they passed up the opportunity to
choose Toni Kukoc, and the Chicago Bulls went on to draft him in
the second round," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
