<HEADLINE> Wang Zhizhi Factfile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China's Wang Zhizhi became the
first Asian basketball player in history ever to be drafted by an
NBA team after the Wednesday's NBA draft in the United States:
</P>
<P>
Following is the factfile about the center:
</P>
<P>
Family name: Wang
</P>
<P>
Given name: Zhizhi (In Chinese means "To rule with most and
extreme")
</P>
<P>
Nickname by teammates and fans: "Big Zhi"
</P>
<P>
Position: Center/Forward
</P>
<P>
Height: 2.12 meters
</P>
<P>
Weight: 115 kilograms
</P>
<P>
Birthdate: July 8 ,1977 (in Beijing, China)
</P>
<P>
CBA (Chinese Basketball Association) team: August First (Bayi)
Rockets
</P>
<P>
Seasons played in CBA: 5
</P>
<P>
Hobbies: Writing; Listening to music; studying English
</P>
<P>
NBA player most like to play one on one with: Hakeem Olajuwon
of Houston Rockets
</P>
<P>
Years in Brief:
</P>
<P>
1985: Started to learn basketball at the age of 8 at the
Beijing Workers Stadium Spare Time Sports School, under the
guidance of his father, Wang Weijun, one of the leading centers in
China in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
1991: Selected by the Junior Team of the August First, the
longtime champion of China's national championship and the
National Games.
</P>
<P>
1993: Recruited by the August adult team when Wang was only 16
but stood at 2.10 meters.
</P>
<P>
1995-1999: played starting center for August First in the test
and first four seasons of the CBA League and won five straight
championships.
</P>
<P>
International experiences:
</P>
<P>
1995: Asian junior championship silver medal winner; World
junior championship 9th place
</P>
<P>
1996: Asian junior championship, gold medal winner; selected to
the world junior all-star team; beat the United States junior
stars at the Nike Summit Championship
</P>
<P>
1996: Atlanta Olympic Games, eighth place (the best ever result
China had at the Olympic Games)
</P>
<P>
1997: China's National Games champion with August First
</P>
<P>
1997: Asian Championship third place
</P>
<P>
1998: Asian Games gold medal winner
</P>
<P>
1999: National Team for the Asian Championship in August
</P>
