<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Industrial Production Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's industrial production value
in the first six months of this year rose 10.3 percent on a
year-on-year basis, the local press Thursday quoted a report of
Vietnam's General Statistics Office as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, the increase was low compared with the 12.6 percent
registered in the first half of last year and 13.6 percent in the
first half of 1997, due to poor performance of the domestic
sector, including both state-owned and non-state-owned
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The foreign-invested sector maintained a high growth rate
thanks to the operation of more projects. The sector posted a
22.6-percent increase in the reviewed period as compared with 23.3
percent of last year's first half.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, enterprises under Vietnam's Ministry of Industry
boosted their production by only 4.4 percent in the first six
months of 1999 while the corresponding figure of last year was
10.1 percent. In the country's two industrial hubs of Hanoi and Ho
Chi Minh City, centrally-run enterprises achieved 6.8 and 4.1
percent increases respectively in production value.
</P>
<P>
The rise was 6.6 percent for the non-state sector, just more
than half of the 11.5-percent growth in the same period of last
year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
