<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Form National AIDS Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vice-Chairman Sobbie Mulindi of Kenya's National AIDS Committee
said the council would be the highest body in dealing with
HIV/AIDS activities, the East African Standard newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mulindi said the council would involve multi-sectors including
 ministries, professionals, non-governmental organizations,
private sector, religious organizations and donor agencies.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the formation of the council is a necessity by
the reality that the prevention and control of HIV/AIDS is no
longer a Ministry of Health affair but is affecting all sectors
of the economy.
</P>
<P>
To assist the council, he said, the government has come up with
a sessional paper on AIDS and will see to it that it is fully
implemented.
</P>
<P>
According to Mulindi, a massive multi-sectoral campaign would
be launched at the grassroots level to sensitize local
communities on HIV/AIDS and effect a change of attitude.
</P>
<P>
HIV/AIDS has been a grave social problem in Kenya and has
seriously affected the country's economic development. It is said
that AIDS orphans in Kenya is expected to reach 580,000 next year
and almost one million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
A latest report prepared by the National AIDS Control Program
says that the cumulative number of AIDS deaths would increase
from the current 100, 000 to one million by 2000 and 2.1 million
by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's Health Permanent Secretary Philemon Mwaisaka said in
mid-June that more than 200,000 Kenyans would die from AIDS
before the end of this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
