<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist Predicts Colder Global Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The latest research on ice cores
from the South Pole suggests that the global climate is entering a
period of transition from warm to cold weather.
</P>
<P>
Colder weather is likely to follow years of global warming,
according to doctor Kang Jiancheng, director of the polar region
office under the Chinese Polar Region Institute.
</P>
<P>
Kang, a member of the research team, recently urged the nation'
s cities, both coastal and inland, to fully consider the influence
global climate changes will have on the construction of
infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
Ice cores from the South Pole are believed to offer an accurate
record of atmospheric conditions over tens of thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
Record of global climate changes over the past 400,000 years
indicate that the world characteristically passes through cool and
warm cycles.
</P>
<P>
The North and South poles and the glacier on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau in southwest China, the world's so-called "third pole,"
are generally considered to be the best areas for obtaining
ancient meteorological information and for conducting
environmental and climatic research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Sea Fishing Moratorium Proceeds Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The first fishing moratorium in
the South China Sea, an initial effort to protect fish resources,
has proceeded smoothly over the past month.
</P>
<P>
Trawling and all forms of net fishing have been banned in area
north of 12 degrees latitude, including the Beibu Gulf between
June 1-July 31.
</P>
<P>
The fleet of over 10,300 trawlers and fishing boats in
Guangdong Province, which has been most affected by the fishing
ban, have remained berthed and fishing licenses have been handed
in to the provincial fisheries administration.
</P>
<P>
The province's 1999 output for aquatic products will drop by
estimated 200,000 tons, or approximately 12 percent of the normal
annual total, as a result of the two-month fishing ban.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen Yiping, the senior official in charge of fishing,
said that over 60 million shrimp and 3.55 million fry fish, valued
10 million yuan, will be released into the South Sea during the
moratorium.
</P>
<P>
Knowledgeable source with the marine aquatics department has
reported an ample supply of related products on the market. Price
has remained basically stable, with overall prices for aquatics
products rising three percent and for sea products by eight
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Economy to Thrive Again: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region said here Thursday
that the worst is over and Hong Kong's economy will thrive again
after a period of consolidation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony for the unveiling of the Monument in
Commemoration of Hong Kong's Return to China Thursday morning,
Tung said: "With the total support of our country, we have fully
and faithfully implemented 'one country, two systems' in
accordance with the Basic Law."
</P>
<P>
For the very first time, he said: "Hong Kong is charting its
own future and our long term development plans with great
expectations."
</P>
<P>
"In the new millennium, we are committed to building Hong Kong
as a modern, civil and knowledge-based society, the metropolis of
the East which embraces innovation and technology and a bridge
linking China with the rest of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As masters of our own destiny, we will meet every challenge,"
he said. "Amidst the Asian financial turmoil, we defended the Hong
Kong financial system with decisive action. During the economic
downturn, we adopted strategies to ride out the storm together
with the people of Hong Kong and invested heavily in
infrastructural developments and education to lay a solid
foundation for our future."
</P>
<P>
"The worst is over. After a period of consolidation, our
economy will thrive again," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Noting the two major celebrations in 1999 -- the 50th
anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic of China and
Macao's return to China, Tung said: "An exquisite picture which
depicts the historical rejuvenation of a nation is unfolding
before the world. I deeply realize that we are an active player in
this historical picture, and not a mere bystander."
</P>
<P>
"The country has entrusted the future and destiny of Hong Kong
to all of us in Hong Kong with the hope that we will be able to
realize a broad vision and work towards a bright future with our
own efforts and wisdom," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I am absolutely confident that this vision will become a
reality because the vast majority of Hong Kong people have this
conviction: the people of Hong Kong are capable of administering
Hong Kong well," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"With this conviction, we will strive to overcome any
difficulty and make progress in furthering the cause of the
Chinese nation," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
