<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italians in Favor But Ignorant of Euro: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Italians are all in favor of Europe's
new single currency, the euro, but not very clear about it, said a
recent poll published Wednesday by the Italian government's Euro
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1,000 people, designed to gauge the knowledge
and feelings of the Italians about the euro, shows that 93.3
percent of the people questioned are comfortable with the name '
euro', while only 1.5 percent still take it as the ECU (European
Currency Unit).
</P>
<P>
Problems arose when the question turned to the currency's value.
Only 13.9 percent correctly answered that it is worth 1.936.27
lire, 15.1 percent came very close to 1.936 lire, 34.5 percent
erred in excess of 100 lire, 10 percent were way off the mark and
26.2 percent didn't know how to respond at all.
</P>
<P>
In Italy, the level of support for the common currency, which
came into being on January 1, 1999, remains very high at 79.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 70 percent of those interviewed said that they have got
their information about the euro from television and radio, and 66.
2 percent said they have seen new awareness campaigns on the
currency in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Some 77 percent said they have noticed the double pricing of
products in both lire and the euro in store windows.
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that 22.4 percent of Italian businesses
have completed the information program linked to the arrival of
the euro, 34.3 percent are on the way, and 33.8 percent were yet
to start. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
