<HEADLINE> HKSAR Publishes 1999 Honor List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A total of 260 persons from all
walks of life in Hong Kong have been accorded an honor or award by
Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa for their significant personal
contribution to Hong Kong or for their dedicated public and
community service.
</P>
<P>
According to the 1999 Honors List published in the Government
Gazette Thursday, 5 persons have won the top award, the Grand
Bauhinia Medal (GBM).
</P>
<P>
Lee Chark-tim, president of the Hong Kong Federation of Trade
Unions, is awarded the GBM for his outstanding contribution to
labor welfare in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued Thursday by the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government said that Lee has also made
a distinguished contribution to the preparatory work for the
establishment of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Anson Chan, administrative secretary for the SAR, won the GBM
for her life-long and dedicated service for the well-being of Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
As head of the civil service since 1993, she has made
outstanding contribution to the smooth transition of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Yang Ti-liang, member of the Executive Council of the HKSAR, is
among the top award recipients for his distinguished public
service, and for his outstanding contribution to the development
of law and order and higher education in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Sidney Gordon, chairman of the Standing Commission on Civil
Service Salaries and Conditions of Service and a former China
Light &AMP; Power chairman, is awarded the GBM for his long and
distinguished public and community service in Hong Kong,
particularly in relation to civil service matters.
</P>
<P>
William Purves, former chairman of the Hongkong Shanghai
Banking Corporation and member of the Council of International
Advisers to the chief executive, got the GBM for his outstanding
contribution to the development of the banking sector in Hong Kong
and for promoting Hong Kong as an international financial center.
</P>
<P>
The other 255 persons on the list are recipients of Gold
Bauhinia Star, Silver Bauhinia Star, Distinguished Service Medals,
Bronze Bauhinia Star, Medal for Bravery, Meritorious Service
Medals, Medal of Honor, Chief Executive's Commendation for
Community Service and Chief Executive's Commendation for
Government/Public Service.
</P>
<P>
This is the second full honors list since Hong Kong returned to
China on July 1, 1997. The presentation ceremony will be held
later this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
