<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Plans Import Tariff Cuts to Boost Purchasing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Finance Ministry of Thailand is
considering cutting import tariffs on luxury goods to help promote
Thailand as a regional shopping center for tourists, the Bangkok
Post said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With millions of tourists visiting Thailand every year, the
measure is expected to help boost tourism revenues, the biggest
source of foreign exchange for the country.
</P>
<P>
New rates for luxury imports would be part of a broader
restructuring plan for the current tariff system, expected to be
considered by the cabinet next month.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministry officials are considering cutting tariffs on
goods such as pens and watches to help bring local prices in line
with those quoted in Singapore and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Some tariffs now are over 50 percent, raised over the past two
years by the government to help curb overconsumption and imports.
</P>
<P>
Wary of the potential impact on the current account and
imports, any new tariff adjustment would likely be to just a
limited group of goods not available or produced locally,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the Finance Ministry also plans to announce
new tax waivers for raw material purchases used by producers for
export goods.
</P>
<P>
Producers would also gain similar tax benefits if goods were
sold to tourists, expected to help reduce retail prices and
promote Thailand as a regional shopping destination.
</P>
<P>
Basic raw materials would be taxed at one percent, intermediate
goods seven percent and finished goods at 15 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
