<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Timor Factions Sign Declaration on Common Principles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Rival factions of East Timor ended
their second-round dialogue here on Wednesday night, signing a
declaration on common principles, including a call on UNAMET (U.N.
Mission in East Timor) to be neutral.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was signed by 30 representatives of the
pro-integration camp and 30 others of pro-independence camp, as
well as by Dili Bishop Carlos Filipe Ximenes Belo, Baucau Bishop
Basilio do Nascimento and U.N. representative Tamrat Samuel.
</P>
<P>
The 16-point declaration dealt with four major matters:
politics, security, reconciliation and the popular consultation on
wide-ranging autonomy status scheduled to be held by the end of
August this year.
</P>
<P>
The declaration said the Indonesian Police Force was the only
authority responsible for security and public order during the
entire popular consultation process, in accordance with the
agreement on May 5, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The May 5 agreement was reached in the tripartite meeting
between Indonesia and Portugal under the auspices of the U.N.
Secretary General in New York. It called for the holding of a
direct ballot as the final solution to the East Timor problem,
while the Indonesian Police would take the responsibility of
maintaining security and order.
</P>
<P>
The ballot would allow about 800,000 East Timorese people to
determine their own future by choosing whether they accept the
wide-ranging autonomy status as offered by Jakarta, or to be
separated from Indonesia to become an independent nation.
</P>
<P>
The declaration agreed to respect the bilateral agreement
signed here on June 18 on disarming the two factions. The
declaration also said both factions agreed to respect the outcome
of the U.N. administered popular consultation.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, the conference participants urged the
Indonesian Armed Forces to be neutral throughout the process of
the popular consultation.
</P>
<P>
The rival factions also urged the UNAMET to maintain its
neutrality throughout the process of the popular consultation.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET has been criticized by several sides, especially by the
pro-integration camp, that it takes sides in carrying out its
duties in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Jailed rebel leader Jose Alexandre "Xanana" Gusmao said that
during the three-day meeting, its 60 participants did their best
to produce a compromise between the East Timorese people and the
Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
The positive contribution the two rival camps had made to the
church-organized conference was an assurance that they were aware
of their responsibility and that they respected the rights of East
Timorese, Gusmao was quoted by Antara News Agency Thursday as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador-at-Large Lopez da Cruz, who headed the
pro-integration camp during the meeting, said it was a beginning
of a long-term reconciliation process.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that before, during and after the August
direct ballot, the situation in East Timor would remain peaceful.
</P>
<P>
Tamrat Samuel said the meeting was the first real gathering of
leaders of the two conflicting factions. They had shown their
commitment to reconciliation despite the fact that none of the
conference participants were expecting reconciliation to be
achieved overnight.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, spokesman for the talks Father Domingos Sequeira
said despite a good atmosphere around the negotiating table, deep
divisions remain between the rival factions.
</P>
<P>
"On the last day of talks, delegates from pro-integration and
pro-independence groups refined a statement of the basic ideas
they can agree on, but could find little common ground on
(establishing) a joint committee for the implementation of these
ideas," he was quoted by Antara as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the most significant achievement of the conference was
an agreement in principle to respect the June 18 agreement on the
disarmament of rival factions.
</P>
<P>
The second-round meeting was a continuation of a successful
church-sponsored conference held in Dare village, west of Dili,
capital of East Timor, in September last year.
</P>
<P>
In the talks last year, the rival factions agreed to recognize
their differing views and refrain from violence.
</P>
<P>
East Timor had been under Portuguese colonial rule for more
than 400 years. It was integrated into Indonesia in 1976 in a move
never recognized by the United Nations, which still considers
Portugal as the administering power of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Seizes 2 Tons of Cocaine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Ecuadorian police have seized more
than two tons of cocaine recently in the north of the country,
press reports said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Patricio Rueta Armendariz, chief of the Rural Service Command
in Pichincha, said the drug seizure was the largest in the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
During the operation, 12 people were arrested and two trucks, a
small bus and two small canoes were confiscated, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Anti-narcotic agents discovered 2,109 packets of cocaine
hydrochloride, with each containing 1.093 kilograms, hidden in two
of the vehicles from Lago Agria, in Sucumbios, Rueta Armendariz
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
