<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banks' Bad Loans Hit New High in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Data from the Philippine Central
Bank showed that commercial banks' nonperforming loan ratio
climbed to 14.48 percent as of April this year, 1.1 percent higher
than the previous month, the Business World reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The April ratio was the highest since the outbreak of the Asian
contagion in 1997. The ratio is computed by dividing the volume of
bad loans by total loans.
</P>
<P>
Despite government efforts to stimulate it, bank lending
remained sluggish, with total loans granted as of April pegged at
1.65 trillion pesos (43.42 billion U.S. dollars), 1.28 percent
less than the 1.484 trillion pesos (39.06 billion dollars) as of
March.
</P>
<P>
"Total loans have been contracting since February. Banks are
still not lending," a banking analyst said.
</P>
<P>
And as the volume of loans contracted, bad loans rose by 8.44
percent to 212.138 billion pesos (5.58 billion dollars) in April,
the highest so far, from 195.635 billion pesos (5.15 billion
dollars) the month before.
</P>
<P>
Restructured loans in April amounted to 52.568 billion pesos
(1.38 billion dollars), 1.24 percent more than the 51.923 billion
pesos (1.37 billion dollars) in March.
</P>
<P>
Loan loss provisions, meanwhile, summed up to 70.458 billion
pesos (1.85 billion dollars) and 67.740 billion pesos (1.78
dollars) in April and March respectively.
</P>
<P>
Last December, commercial banks' bad loans tapered off slightly
to 10.37 percent of total loans, from 11.78 percent a month ago.
It has since steadily been rising beginning January this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
