<HEADLINE> Formula One Needs Time to Study EC Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Formula One Management Ltd, the
company which runs the motor race, said on Wednesday that it
needed more time to study a document from the European Commission
starting legal proceedings against it and the FIA world motor
racing body on grounds of anti-competitive behavior.
</P>
<P>
"It is too soon for the company to have assimilated the
contents of the document, however, the company welcomes that the
EU has at last stated its position," Formula One Management Ltd
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Formula One Management, owned by Bernie Ecclestone, sells
broadcasting rights for Grand Prix races.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission earlier said it had started the
proceedings against the FIA and Formula One on suspicion that they
breached EU competition rules.
</P>
<P>
"The Commission has now formally told the Federation
Internationale de l'Automobile (FIA)...that it considers the FIA
to be abusing its dominant position and restricting competition,"
the Commission said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Formula One said it had told the Commission "on a number of
occasions" that concerns previously expressed about certain
restrictions in the promoters' and broadcasters' contracts had
been dealt with.
</P>
<P>
It also said it was "gravely concerned" that a journalist had
an advance copy of the confidential Commission document before
itself.
</P>
<P>
"The company is considering the implications of this," it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
