<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: Asian Crisis Hits Bottom, Recovery Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Two years after a financial crisis
threw Asia into an economic turmoil, economies in the region are
now showing more and more signs of recovering from a deep
recession.
</P>
<P>
On July 2, 1997, the decision by the Bank of Thailand to float
the baht triggered a financial storm, which soon spread onto the
rest of the region. Currencies in Southeast Asian nations and
South Korea depreciated by 15 to 80 percent in the course of the
upheaval; stock markets in most part of Asia nose-dived by over 50
percent; foreign exchange reserves of the crisis-hit nations were
depleted to the lowest level in a decade...
</P>
<P>
With the deterioration of the crisis, dozens of banks
collapsed, thousands of companies closed, millions of people lost
their jobs and lived below the poverty line in the region. Asia,
once the fast growing region in the world, saw many countries
falling into a severe recession in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the crisis caused social unrest in Thailand, South
Korea and Indonesia and forced leadership shakeups in these
countries.
</P>
<P>
But now, on the second anniversary of the crisis, the financial
fires are out, the smoke over Asia is clearing. Asia's economic
picture has improved greatly, and the region is growing again.
</P>
<P>
"There is every reason to believe that the (Asian) countries
will successfully overcome the crisis and that a year from now we
will have a full-fledged recover," said Hubert Neiss, IMF
(International Monetary Fund) Asia-Pacific Director, at a recent
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Neiss' assessment is identical with that of many economists,
who believe that the two-year old crisis has hit the bottom and
Asia has embarked on the road to recovery.
</P>
<P>
The most convincing sign of the recovery has come from the
financial market, whose turmoil was considered one of the direct
causes of the economic meltdown in the region two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, Asia's financial market has
remained relatively stable despite the launch of the euro,
Brazil's financial crisis and the unstable exchange rate of the
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
However, a new round of financial storms did not break out as
many people had expected. On the contrary, Asian currencies have
appreciated steadily in the past six months.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian rupiah, which depreciated to 14,750 to the U.S.
dollar in June 1998 from 2,390 in February 1997, has rebounded to
around 7,000 now. The Thai baht has rose to around 37 against the
greenback from 57 during the worst part of the crisis in the first
half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Stocks in Asian countries have recovered by 30 to 50 percent,
near the pre-crisis levels, and continued their upturns.
</P>
<P>
Government officials in the crisis-hit countries are confident
that the rising foreign exchange reserves and current account
surplus could prevent a new around of a financial turmoil even if
the U.S. Federal Reserve Board raises interest rates.
</P>
<P>
With the stabilization of the financial market, economic
reforms and measures to stimulate the growth by Asian countries
have pushed the region's economy to the stage of recovery.
</P>
<P>
In the first quarter of this year, gross domestic product (GDP)
grew by 4.6 percent in South Korea, 1.2 percent in the Philippines
and Singapore, compared to contractions in 1998. Malaysia's GDP
also increased by 1.4 percent in February and March, although it
declined in January.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank predicted that the economy in the
developing Asia could increase 4.4 percent this year, and 5.1
percent next year, from 2.6 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
"I think the recovery is sustainable. Exports are picking up.
Inflation is contained. Interest rates are the lowest in two
decades. Foreign reserves have been increasing steadily. The
current account has been in surplus consecutively for over a year.
Foreign investment is coming back. International confidence is
improving," said Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan at the
annual corporate conference of the Far East Economic Review last
month.
</P>
<P>
All these factors mentioned by the Thai official have paved the
way for a full-fledged recovery in Asia and could help the
stabilization of political situation in the crisis-affected
nations.
</P>
<P>
Except Indonesia, most Asian countries have become quiet as far
as the internal situation is concerned. This, in turn, has
provided favorable social environment for an economic surge.
</P>
<P>
However, the region's economic recovery is just at the initial
stage. Without further reforms in the banking sector and the
corporate sector, Asia will need much longer time to regain its
economic strength, economists warned.
</P>
<P>
Asia, in the aftermath of the crisis, still has a long way to
go toward a full recovery. This is the general consensus of
opinions by almost all economists. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
