<HEADLINE> Private Firms Gain Foreign Trade Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China had granted import-export
trade rights to 142 private enterprises since the beginning of
this year, when the work began.
</P>
<P>
A varying number of private firms in most of the nation's
provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions have gained such
trade rights.
</P>
<P>
A private firm in southwest China's Guizhou Province was
granted with the import-export trade right early last month,
according to an official with the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC). It is the first to obtain such a
right in the province.
</P>
<P>
The official also noted that northwest China's Qinghai Province
is awaiting approval of its first firm to get the right.
</P>
<P>
The total 1998 export volume for the aforementioned 142 firms
hit 450 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The firms come from the sectors of industries, including
animal feed, wood and mineral processing, foodstuffs, chemicals,
agriculture, construction materials, textile, electronics and
machinery.
</P>
<P>
Applicants are required to have registered capital of at least
8.50 million yuan (some one million US dollars) and an annual
turnover of 50 million yuan. Electronic companies must have an
annual turnover of at least 30 million yuan, with the figure for
machinery standing at 10 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
A large number of private firms are anxiously awaiting a
relaxation of requirements for import-export trade rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
