<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers Praise Self-Study Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Zhou Wang, a 35-year-old farmer
from Zhouchan Village in east China's Zhejiang Province, recently
reached a personal milestone by completing a self-study program
and earning a three-year college equivalency certificate.
</P>
<P>
Zhou had long dreamed of becoming a university graduate, but
was ineligible for the college entrance examination, which is
limited to individuals under the age of 25.
</P>
<P>
Some 40 Zhouchan villagers followed Zhou's lead and have since
participated in the self-study program, which provides a large
number of rural residents to attain higher levels of education.
</P>
<P>
China introduced the self-study exam system in 1981. The system
is free of restrictions related to place of birth, sex, age,
nationality and level of education. Chinese citizens have praised
the education system which was introduced in rural areas beginning
in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
China's colleges and universities had a total enrollment of 1.3
million students in 1998, with an 11 million people, mostly rural,
completing self-study examinations during the year.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang Province has established examination centers in 552,
or 30 percent, of its total villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
Some 500,000 Zhejiang residents completed the self-study exam
in 1998 alone, with the number of rural residents participating in
the program soaring from only four percent in 1991 to over 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
Tens of thousands of rural residents in Zhejiang have earned
college equivalency certificates. The vast majority of program
graduates have remained in their hometowns and have developed into
the backbone force for local production and management.
</P>
<P>
Modern agricultural production relies heavily on technological
expertise and the program provides farmers with an avenue for self-
improvement, according to fruit grower Cheng Handing. Cheng said
the self-study program has provided rich returns and enabled him
to apply knowledge gained from related studies to his orchard
operations.
</P>
<P>
A four-year college education currently costs an estimated 40,
000 yuan for a student, while the total cost for a self-study
student stands at only 1,700 yuan, of which 1,500 yuan paid by
participants in the self-study program. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
