<HEADLINE> Thai State Agencies Streamlined: Seminar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- About 6,000 jobs for permanent
government officials and 4,000 state employees in Thailand have
been eliminated as a result of the country's bureaucratic reform,
a seminar said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Attended by 300 senior government officials, the seminar, began
on Wednesday, said that bureaucratic reform has progressed since
cabinet approved the process in May.
</P>
<P>
Abhisit Vejajiva, minister of Prime Minister's Office and also
vice-chairman of the bureaucratic system reform committee, told
the seminar, which aims to examine the progress of the reform,
that the Public Organization Bill, which reforms the system of
public administration, had also been promulgated.
</P>
<P>
The bureaucratic reform plan deals with five areas, including
improving the budgetary system and boosting efficiency in
personnel administration, Abhisit said.
</P>
<P>
New regulations and performance evaluation were being drafted
to screen out unproductive employees, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the current system, which focuses on job security for
government officials, was not in the public interest.
</P>
<P>
Government agencies were also urged to take the voluntary early
retirement scheme seriously.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet has approved an early retirement package, aiming to
cut the state workforce by at least 120,000 jobs in the next three
years, including 30,000 by October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
