<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Strives to Remove Leprosy Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A high-ranking Myanmar health
official has called for removal of leprosy from the public health
problems in the country, while striving to reduce the number of
leprosy infected persons.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health Major-General Ket Sein said at a seminar
here Wednesday on leprosy education that there are now only over
10,000 leprosy patients in Myanmar, down from over 200,000 in
1987.
</P>
<P>
The authorities were exposing and giving treatment from 6,000
to 10,000 leprosy patients annually in the past, he disclosed.
</P>
<P>
He added that efforts are underway to wipe out leprosy disease
from the nation by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar is giving priority in the health sector to combat the
disease as a public health problem. Pilot trials were initiated in
epidemic areas and anti-leprosy campaigns were started in 1951
which covered the whole country by the end of 1968.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1977, there registered 270,000 leprosy cases in
Myanmar, the highest number of the cases at one period in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Up to 1988, 33,875 of cases were reported discharged as cured.
</P>
<P>
With the introduction of Multi Drug Treatment by the World
Health Organization in 1989, 120,057 patients were also
reportedly cured up to the end of 1993.
</P>
<P>
Later, Myanmar worked out a two-phase National Leprosy
Elimination Project (1993-96 and 1996-2001). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0322 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State-run Corporations Suffer Heavy Losses in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Six state-run industrial corporations
in Bangladesh, which earned a total profit of 605.7 million taka
(12.49 million U.S. dollars) between July 1992 and June 30 this
year, suffered a colossal loss of 41,102.8 million taka (847.48
million dollars) during the same period, The New Nation daily
newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The corporations are the Bangladesh Textiles Mills Corporation
(BTMC), the Bangladesh Steel and Engineering Corporation, the
Bangladesh Sugar and Food Industries Corporation (BSFIC), the
Bangladesh Chemical Industries Corporation (BCIC), the Bangladesh
Forest Industries Development Corporation and the Bangladesh Jute
Mils Corporation (BJMC).
</P>
<P>
The projected profit and loss of these corporations during the
1998-99 fiscal year ending on June 30 have been estimated at 61
million taka (1.26 million dollars) and 6,767 million taka (139.53
million dollars) respectively.
</P>
<P>
Of the six corporations, the BJMC has an accumulated loss of
15,494.4 million taka (319.47 million dollars), followed by the
BTMC of 8,946.2 million taka (184.46 million dollars). The three
corporations did not earn a single taka profit during the period
under review.
</P>
<P>
The BSFIC made a profit of 25.3 million taka (0.52 million
dollars) in 1994-95 only, and incurred a loss of 378 million taka
(7.79 million dollars) the following year.
</P>
<P>
The BCIC, which earned a profit of 205.8 million taka (4.24
million dollars) in 1992-93 and 254.9 million taka (5.26 million
dollars) in 1993-94, started losing heavily in subsequent years.
It has a projected loss of 1,674 million taka (34.52 million
dollars) during the just-ended 1998-99 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Early this year, the Bangladeshi government decided to
privatize 51 state-owned enterprises (SOEs) under the BTMC, the
BJMC, the BSFIC, the BSEC and the BCIC respectively, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
There are about 300 SOEs in the country, with a total value of
output accounting for about 6 percent of the gross domestic
product and incurring a loss of about 568 million U.S. dollars
every year, reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
