<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientist Predicts Colder Global Climate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The latest research on ice cores
from the South Pole suggests that the global climate is entering a
period of transition from warm to cold weather.
</P>
<P>
Colder weather is likely to follow years of global warming,
according to doctor Kang Jiancheng, director of the polar region
office under the Chinese Polar Region Institute.
</P>
<P>
Kang, a member of the research team, recently urged the nation'
s cities, both coastal and inland, to fully consider the influence
global climate changes will have on the construction of
infrastructure facilities.
</P>
<P>
Ice cores from the South Pole are believed to offer an accurate
record of atmospheric conditions over tens of thousands of years.
</P>
<P>
Record of global climate changes over the past 400,000 years
indicate that the world characteristically passes through cool and
warm cycles.
</P>
<P>
The North and South poles and the glacier on the Qinghai-Tibet
Plateau in southwest China, the world's so-called "third pole,"
are generally considered to be the best areas for obtaining
ancient meteorological information and for conducting
environmental and climatic research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0325 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Sea Fishing Moratorium Proceeds Smoothly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The first fishing moratorium in
the South China Sea, an initial effort to protect fish resources,
has proceeded smoothly over the past month.
</P>
<P>
Trawling and all forms of net fishing have been banned in area
north of 12 degrees latitude, including the Beibu Gulf between
June 1-July 31.
</P>
<P>
The fleet of over 10,300 trawlers and fishing boats in
Guangdong Province, which has been most affected by the fishing
ban, have remained berthed and fishing licenses have been handed
in to the provincial fisheries administration.
</P>
<P>
The province's 1999 output for aquatic products will drop by
estimated 200,000 tons, or approximately 12 percent of the normal
annual total, as a result of the two-month fishing ban.
</P>
<P>
However, Chen Yiping, the senior official in charge of fishing,
said that over 60 million shrimp and 3.55 million fry fish, valued
10 million yuan, will be released into the South Sea during the
moratorium.
</P>
<P>
Knowledgeable source with the marine aquatics department has
reported an ample supply of related products on the market. Price
has remained basically stable, with overall prices for aquatics
products rising three percent and for sea products by eight
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Wang Picked by Dallas Mavericks in NBA Draft ( Updated) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Chinese center Wang Zhizhi has
been picked 36th in the second round of the National Basketball
Association draft by Dallas Mavericks on Wednesday to become the
first Asian basketball player in history ever to be drafted by an
NBA team.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who is 2.12 meters tall and weighs 115 kilograms,
averaged 11.1 points and 5.6 rebounds for China at the Atlanta
Olympic Games in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who turns 22 on July 8, plays for China's five-time
national champion Bayi Rockets.
</P>
<P>
He led China's CBA league by blocking last season and was third
in scoring.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of the Dallas Mavericks, I'm so glad that we will
have the chance to work with Wang Zhizhi because he's a young
basketball player with great talent," said Donn Nelson, head coach
of the Dallas Mavericks, in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"His draft story will remind basketball fans of Toni Kukoc,
Dino Radja, Drazen Petrovic, Cedric Cegallos P.J. Brown,. and even
Dennis Rodman, all of whom succeeded after being drafted at the
same position as Wang," Nelson added.
</P>
<P>
As the first NBA coach ever visited China, Nelson spent nine
days in Beijing and Shanghai last summer and had basketball
clinics for Chinese Basketball Association (CBA) coaches, Junior
Team, Pro team, and young kids.
</P>
<P>
"Two things made me fall in love with this country, great
people and the love Chinese people give to the game," Nelson said.
"I found that the potential of basketball in China is huge; the
CBA has done a great job of making this game popular in China. The
game will become much more popular sport in the country with the
drafting of Wang into NBA."
</P>
<P>
"I'm very happy to see that China has produced the first Asian
basketball player to make the NBA," Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
But Nelson said the Mavericks will respect CBA's decision if
they do not allow Wang to play in NBA very soon.
</P>
<P>
He said: "I know it might be difficult for Wang to come out and
play in the NBA very soon since the Army Club might need him to
stay and carry the team for a couple of more years. The Mavericks
will respect the special situation of China basketball and Army
basketball."
</P>
<P>
Nelson added: "But the reason we drafted him is that Wang
deserves this pick because of his basketball skills and potential,
and I hope this young person will have the chance to make his hoop
dream come true soon.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't want to make the same mistake that the Golden State
Warriors made in 1990 when they passed up the opportunity to
choose Toni Kukoc, and the Chicago Bulls went on to draft him in
the second round," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
