<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic News Summary at 0630 GMT, July 1 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME -- The Italian government Wednesday evening approved the
four-year economic plan, entailing a lighter budget for next year
than originally expected with no mention of highly controversial
pension cuts.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 budget was put at 15 trillion lire (8 billion U.S.
dollars), comprising 11.5 trillion lire in cuts, with the ax
falling heavily on the public employment sector and regional
health spending, and 3.5 trillion lire in spending designed to
boost growth. (Italy-Economic Plan)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- Cuba will adopt the euro as of July 1 in business
with the European Union.
</P>
<P>
The use of the single European currency will make it easier
for Cuba to conduct international business as the U.S. blockade of
the country discourages the use of the dollar, said Francisco
Soberon, President of the Central Bank of Cuba. (Cuba-Euro)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
QUITO -- Visiting Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar said
here Wednesday that he had called on the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) President Michel Camdessus to help Ecuador settle its
foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
At a joint press conference held with his Ecuadorian
counterpart Jamil Mahuad, Aznar said that world organizations such
as the IMF, the World Bank and the Inter-American Development Bank
should help Ecuador tide over the crisis. (Spain-Ecuador-IMF)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italians are all in favor of Europe's new single
currency, the euro, but not very clear about it, said a recent
poll published Wednesday by the Italian government's Euro
Committee.
</P>
<P>
The survey of 1,000 people, designed to gauge the knowledge and
feelings of the Italians about the euro, shows that 93.3 percent
of the people questioned are comfortable with the name "euro,"
while only 1.5 percent still take it as the ECU (European Currency
Unit). (Italy-Euro-Survey)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- The Finance Ministry of Thailand is considering
cutting import tariffs on luxury goods to help promote Thailand as
a regional shopping center for tourists, the Bangkok Post said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
With millions of tourists visiting Thailand every year, the
measure is expected to help boost tourism revenues, the biggest
source of foreign exchange for the country.
</P>
<P>
New rates for luxury imports would be part of a broader
restructuring plan for the current tariff system, expected to be
considered by the cabinet next month. (Thailand-Tariff )  
</P>
</TEXT>
