<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Research Breakthroughs Expected by China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xu Guanhua, vice minister of Science and Technology, said that
over half of the programs are focused on subjects which were
introduced this year and 32 programs cover the high-tech sector.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Xu said that the 51 programs cover
agro-science, high technology and social development fields.
</P>
<P>
He said the agro-science programs include industrialization of
high-yield crop seeds, processing of farm produce and high-
efficient agricultural demonstration projects.
</P>
<P>
The high-tech sector programs cover engineering technology,
high-performance digital exchanges, high-performance concurrent
computer systems, key software technology and the application and
development of new pesticides.
</P>
<P>
The social development research programs include new
pharmaceuticals, medium-term forecasts of violent earthquakes,
short-term forecasts of bad weather and oil prospecting in the
Tarim Basin in northwest China's Xingjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The vice minister said the programs are aimed at encouraging
the upgrading of industrial enterprises, developing high value-
added and competitive products, and meeting the requirements of
the country's long-term sustainable development strategy.
</P>
<P>
China's ninth five-year science and technology plan (1996-2000)
has covered a total of 240 programs with each receiving an average
80 million yuan (9.6 million U.S. dollars) of research funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
