<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malawi Postpones Local Government Polls to 2000 a 070101 Malawi Postpones Local Govt. Polls to 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The electoral commission in Malawi
has postponed local government polls originally scheduled in
September till 2000, a report reaching here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a local government preparatory meeting Wednesday,
the commission chair, Justice James Kalaile, said the commission
has decided to shift the local elections in order to iron out
technical problems.
</P>
<P>
"Our technical advisers have told us that we need the whole
country redemarcated as most parts of the country are not on the
national map," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kalaile added that work on the local elections is already
underway. Most of the 160,000 U.S. dollars needed for the
demarcation exercise and another 300,000 dollars required for
registration of voters had already been secured from donors.
</P>
<P>
He said the commission would like to avoid the mistakes which
threatened to derail the June 15 general elections. The commission
plans to computerize the registration exercise to make it
difficult to tamper with.
</P>
<P>
In order to conduct hitch-free polls, the commission needed
enough time despite earlier arrangements that the local polls be
held three months after the general elections, Kalaile added.
</P>
<P>
He also said the local polls cannot be held during the rain
season, which starts in October, because many parts of the country
will be inaccessible. This will mean the polls not being held
before April 2000.
</P>
<P>
Malawi has had no local authorities since 1994 when the ruling
United Democratic Front dissolved all previous local authorities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
