<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 07:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Foil Alleged Hamas Kidnaping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Israeli military police have
foiled what they suspected of an attempt by the Islamic militant
group Hamas to kidnap Israeli soldiers, local media reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday afternoon, three policewomen patrolling at a
hitchhiking station near a military base south of Tel Aviv found a
silver Subaru suspicious when they overheard the conversation
between the driver and a soldier who asked for a lift, the Haaretz
daily said.
</P>
<P>
The driver, who wore a skullcap popular among Jewish males,
pronounced the Jewish name "Jabotinsky" with a heavy Arabic accent
and he and two back-seat passengers all wore uniforms of the
Israeli Air Force, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
After the policewomen prevented the soldier from getting in,
the car sped away. A police chopper was sent to comb the area, but
found no sign of the car.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli army believed that the three men were members of a
Hamas cell that was trying to kidnap Israeli soldiers, The
Jerusalem Post daily quoted a military police official as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hamas, which opposes the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks and
has staged bombing attacks against Israel, has warned of its
intention to kidnap Israeli soldiers to use as bargaining chips
to trade for the release of Hamas members jailed in Israel.
</P>
</TEXT>
