</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Northern Ireland's peace talks are continuing despite
the passing of the Wednesday midnight "absolute " deadline set by
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, without any sign of a
breakthrough on the issue of guerrilla disarmament which has
paralyzed the province's peace process.
</P>
<P>
Throughout Wednesday, Blair and Irish Prime Minister Bertie
Ahern, his co-broker at the talks, put pressure on Sinn Fein and
the Unionists to shift ground so they could reach a compromise,
sources close to the talks said. (UK-NIreland-Peace)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
VIENNA -- A summit of central and eastern European countries,
which will be dominated by the Kosovo issue, opened in the
Austrian city of Salzburg Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The World Economic Forum (WEF) regional meeting will also
discuss the enlargement of the European Union and review the
drastic changes which began ten years ago in the former Soviet
Union and the eastern European countries.
</P>
<P>
Presidents and prime ministers from 16 central and eastern
European states, representatives of some international
organizations as well as some businessmen attended the three-day
summit, the fourth such annual meeting. (WEF-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- UNCHR Special Envoy Dennis McNamara Wednesday called
on the returned refugees in Kosovo to stop attacking the Serb and
Gypsy population in Kosovo, the Albanian Telegraphic Agency (ATA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
ATA quoted the UNCHR (U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees)
office in Tirana as saying that McNamara indicated that there were
"reports of threats and violent attacks against the Serb and Gypsy
minorities in Kosovo" during the past two weeks and the envoy
requested these actions should end.
</P>
<P>
McNamara also urged the international peace keeping forces in
Kosovo to take security measures to protect the minority
population in Kosovo according to the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 1244, ATA said. (UNCHR-Envoy-Kosovo) 
</P>
