<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Arctic Expedition Ship Weighs Anchor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shanghai: The Snow Dragon, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China's first
scientific expedition to the North Pole kicked off today as the "
Snow Dragon", an ultra-modern icebreaker carrying 124 scientists
and journalists, weighed anchor from a dock in Shanghai this
morning and turned her head towards the Yellow Sea ready to sail
to the polar wastelands.
</P>
<P>
The expedition will take two months, and the scientists are
expected to return to Shanghai on September 1st.
</P>
<P>
Several days of heavy rain in Shanghai ended this morning and
Zhang Dengyi, the director of the State Oceanic Administration,
along with more than 200 officials, students and Shanghai citizens
were at the dock to bid farewell to the expedition team.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the expedition from Shanghai Wenying Primary
School, the kids warned the scientists and journalists to watch
out for polar bears.
</P>
<P>
Chen Liqi, the expedition's chief scientist, said before the
ship left that his team will study the effect of the North Pole on
the global climate, especially on China, the ecological system in
Arctic waters, and the atmosphere, geology, fishing, and marine
environment of the area.
</P>
<P>
"As opposed to the South Pole, the North Pole exerts an
influence on China, as it is located in the northern hemisphere.
As a result of this trip Chinese scientists should be able to
increase their knowledge of the climate and environment in the
Arctic region," said Chen.
</P>
<P>
He added that China intends to actively take part in extensive
scientific research of the polar region while at the same time
protecting yet peacefully exploiting the natural resources there.
</P>
<P>
According to the expedition plan, the ship will pass through
the Sea of Japan, the Bering Sea, and on into the Canada Basin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0358 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
