<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Advances Privatization of Communication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned giant Kenya Posts
and Telecommunications Corporation (KPTC) ceases to exist
Thursday as a milestone of the privatization process began in
1995, Kenya Transport and Communications Ministry announced.
</P>
<P>
The three new corporate bodies born from the former KPTC are
Telkom Kenya Limited, the Postal Corporation of Kenya and the
Communications Commission of Kenya (CCK), the regulator which has
been operational for some time.
</P>
<P>
Telkom Kenya Limited, which took over telecommunications
business of the KPTC, has begun its work, the company's managing
director office said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Telkom Wednesday received its 25-year license and
instruments of mandate from the CCK, the office said.
</P>
<P>
"It is not clear who will buy the Telkom or buy the shares of
the company, " the office also said.
</P>
<P>
"Some 18,000 employees out of the KPTC's work force of 24,000
go to the Telkom, the rest will continue work for the other two
units", the office said, adding that the split of the KPTC is not
expected to cause job losses.
</P>
<P>
Genesius Kithinji, head of the posts and telecommunications
department at the ministry said Wednesday that there will be no
delays in the privatization of the communication sector.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a nine-member transitional management committee has
been formed to help wind up the KPTC, dealing with its
liabilities and disputes, according to a recent special issue of
the Kenya Gazette. The committee comprised of high-ranking
officials will remain in office until the completion, the Kenya
Gazette said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
