<HEADLINE> "The Result Is Acceptable," Russian Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
SAN JOSE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Russian team lost to China 2-0
in the quarterfinals and were eliminated from the 3rd women's World
Cup soccer tournament on Wednesday, but the Russian team coach said
the result was just acceptable.
</P>
<P>
Ury Bistritsky, head coach of the Russian team, said his team's
overall objective was to qualify for the 2000 Sydney Olympic
Games:"So the important thing for us is not to concede too many
goals because the goal of going to Sydney Olympics is at stake."
</P>
<P>
Bistritsky said:"We didn't play as strong as China tonight. We
realized that China would attack us and pile up pressure and we had
to face off to stand up to all the pressure. In the long run, we
don't feel that this is a bad result."
</P>
<P>
Bistritsky complaint that his team lacked prepration for the
World Cup:"Our team had no opportunity or any chance to prepare for
a tournament like this in the way China or the American team can.
We only had five or six days of training before we began competing
in the tournament and that's not the way of doing it properly."
</P>
<P>
Russian goal-keeper Svetlana Petko said the result was
reasonable:"Being realists, we realized China would be the stronger
side. We proceeded from this assumption when preparing for the game
and building up the plan."
</P>
<P>
"If we try to attack early in the game, the result would have
been quite different, not just 0-2. This was the determining factor
in selecting our tactics." said the goal-keeper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
