<HEADLINE> Air Macao May See Profit in First Half of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Preliminary figures have shown that
Air Macao might have turned losses into profits in the first half
of the year, according to sources with the airline company.
</P>
<P>
Affected by the adverse economic environment in surrounding
countries and regions, Air Macao suffered losses in 1998 but the
actual sum was not available.
</P>
<P>
Between January and June this year, the company operated a
total of 4,894 flights carrying more than 592,000 passengers and 6,
800 tons of cargo. Passenger and freight transportation rose 15.63
percent and 6.46 percent respectively over the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
During the six months, the passenger load factor was 66.9
percent which was uplifted 9.5 percent over the same period of
last year.
</P>
<P>
It is expected that the operation of Air Macao will further
improve in the latter half of the year as Macao will have more
exchanges with the outside world in the course of its return to
the motherland.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Air Macao plans to boost its air route between
Macao and Kunming City in southwestern China in mid-July. There
will be two flights per week instead of the present one flight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
