<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Irish Talks to Resume At Noon Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Northern Ireland's peace talks,
adjourned until later in the day on the deadlock of guerrilla
disarmament, will resume at noon, with British Prime Minister Tony
Blair to remain on hand.
</P>
<P>
The talks were called off after nearly 18 hours of non-stop
negotiations and four hours after a Wednesday midnight deadline
originally set by Blair for an agreement that would keep last year
's Good Friday peace accord alive.
</P>
<P>
Rivaling politicians from the British province's majority
Protestant and minority Roman Catholic communities were deadlocked
over how and when guerrillas will turn in their weapons.
</P>
<P>
The deadlock is blocking formation of a power-sharing
provincial administration, a cornerstone of the Good Friday accord.
Unionists refuse to sit in a cabinet with Sinn Fein until the IRA
sheds its weaponry.
</P>
<P>
The Irish Republican Army's (IRA) political wing Sinn Fein made
a new offer after the midnight deadline expired to try to achieve
disarmament by May 2000, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Details of the new Sinn Fein offer were not known but sources
said it amounted to a commitment that IRA disarmament would begin
by October, on condition that the Unionists accept the immediate
admission of Sinn Fein into a coalition executive.
</P>
<P>
Unionists, however, were demanding that disarmament should be
simultaneous with the formation of the executive.
</P>
<P>
Lights burned through the early hours at the sprawling, red-
brick Castle Buildings complex where Blair and his co-broker,
Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern, tried to get an agreement,
Reuters said.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton joined the efforts, phoning the
negotiators in an effort to help secure a deal, according to
earlier reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
