<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Soars on U.S. Fed Rate Stance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar shot higher
Thursday, gaining almost one U.S. cent following strength in
commodity prices and the U.S. Federal Reserve's decision to lift
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
The Australian currency's momentum pushed it to a peak of 67.1
U.S. cents after it recouped more than half a U.S. cent overnight.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar closed at 66.86 U.S. cents from 66.01
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The Australian dollar had a very good day today in a
continuation from last night's move up on the back of the U.S.
rate hike and with the Fed back on hold," Michael Sarpi, head of
foreign exchange sales at Commonwealth Bank, said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Federal Reserve raised its funds rate by 25 basis
points to 5 percent in a widely-anticipated move Wednesday night
but, more importantly for future trends, moved its monetary policy
bias back to neutral.
</P>
<P>
Sarpi said it was also a commodity price story for the
Australian dollar on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Commodity Research Bureau index, a measure of the health of
commodity prices internationally, was up 2.17 points to 191.54
Wednesday night on strong rises in oil and copper prices.
</P>
<P>
Also at the close, the Australian dollar was trading at 64.46
euro cents from 63.86 and 80.78 Japanese yen from 79.78. 
</P>
</TEXT>
