<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Records 571,000 HIV/AIDS Infections in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria had an estimated 571,036
cases of HIV infection and AIDS in 1998, averaging 1,500 new
infections daily, a health official said.
</P>
<P>
National Co-ordinator of the National AIDS Control Program
(NASCAP), Nasir Sani-Gwarzo made these disclosures Wednesday at a
training workshop for health correspondents in Ogun State, western
Nigeria, This Day reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that the HIV prevalence in Nigeria stood at 3.1 million
last year and was expected to hit 5.5 million in the year of 2004.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 139,282 adults died of full-blown AIDS last year
with 158, 598 new adult AIDS cases recorded in 1998, according to
the co-ordinator.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the new AIDS cases in children in 1998 were
55,636 while an estimated new cases among women were 79,299 last
year.
</P>
<P>
The first two AIDS cases were reported in the most populous
African country in 1986. Under the 1991/92 survey, 1.4 percent of
the adult population were infected, which rose to 3.8 percent in
1993/94. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
