<HEADLINE> Philippines to Crack Down on Cutting of Coconut Trees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
create an inter-agency task force that would apprehend those for
illegal felling of coconut trees, an official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Coconut Authority (PCA) Administrator Eduardo
Escueta told reporters that the task force will comprise the
Philippine National Police and Coast Guards.
</P>
<P>
There is a need for the government to stop illegal cutting of
coconut trees, estimated at 1.5 million trees per year, to improve
the nation's coconut production, he said.
</P>
<P>
Escueta said last year's El Nino drought resulted in a 40
percent drop in coconut production in the Philippines and the
country should crack down on any illegal cutting of coconut trees
now.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 3 million hectares of coconut trees
sprawling in 67 of the country's 77 provinces, with 240 million
trees bearing an annual average of 7 billion nuts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Coconut earns the country about 800 million U.S. dollars
annually from exports of coconut products and by-products.
</P>
<P>
About 20 million Filipinos, or nearly one-third of the
country's population, are working in the coconut industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
