<HEADLINE> Indonesia Posts Fourth Monthly Deflation in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia posted a 0.34 percent
deflation or negative inflation in June, the country's fourth
month of deflation in a row, according to the Central Bureau of
Statistics (BPS) Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The negative monthly inflation rate was primarily caused by a
decline in the prices of most basic food commodities, Chief of the
BPS Sugito Suwito told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said a 0.02 percent drop in the prices of processed foods,
beverages, cigarettes and tobacco and a 1.24 percent drop in the
prices of clothing had contributed to the deflation.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia posted a deflation of 0.18 percent in March, 0.68
percent in April and 0.28 percent in May.
</P>
<P>
The government earlier projected an inflation target of 17
percent for the current fiscal year ending March next year, but
recently revised it to 10 percent following positive development
in the country's macroeconomic picture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
