<HEADLINE> ADB's Project Boosts Philippines' Poverty Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 1 (Xinhua) - The Philippine government's thrust of
reducing poverty gets a further boost with the implementation of a
6.2-billion-peso (160-million-U.S. Dollar) project of the Asian
Development Bank (ADB).
</P>
<P>
According to Philippine News Agency, the seven-year project is
designed for agrarian reform communities (ARC) in the country
which comprise about 10 percent of the rural poor.
</P>
<P>
These communities remain without much needed infrastructure
such as farm-to-market roads, potable water and communal
irrigation.
</P>
<P>
About 28,000 households in 140 ARCs will directly benefit from
investments in agriculture and rural infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The incremental increase in farm income is estimated at 36
percent. Some 17,000 person-years of incremental employment will
be generated.
</P>
<P>
The ADB-funded project has four components: rural
infrastructure, land survey for about 100,000 hectares of public
land, development of support services and project management.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of subprojects will be the responsibility of
the local government. Three area project offices will be
established for technical support. 
</P>
</TEXT>
