<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0434 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Health Organization Worried About Polio in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO)
has expressed its concern over the polio situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Luis Sambo, WHO regional chief for Africa, said in Luanda that
Angola is one of the five countries with great difficulty in
making children nationwide to have access to the anti-polio
vaccination.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization has set a target to eliminate the
disease by the year of 2000 and Angola would be unable to achieve
the target, the Journal of Angola Thursday quoted Sambo as saying
here.
</P>
<P>
Sambo, who arrived in Luanda Wednesday on a five-day working
visit, attributed the failure in Angola's anti-polio campaign
largely to the prolonged civil war in the southern African
country.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the Angolan government has been working
hard with the international organizations and it launched three
nationwide anti-polio drives since 1997.
</P>
<P>
The WHO official pointed out that the renewed civil war has not
only negatively affected the immunization campaign, but also
created the chance for the recurrence of the disease in Angola.
This obviously referred to the quickly increased polio cases in
Angola in late March this year.
</P>
<P>
Sambo who is an Angolan, said that during his stay in Angola,
he will discuss with the Angolan health authorities about the
cooperative programs between the WHO and Angola in the coming two
years.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that due to the influx of refugees with
unidentified virus from remote areas, some 1,000 children had so
far been inflicted with some kind of polio caused by the virus and
most of them had become paralyzed for life while more than 100
died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
