talks over Northern Ireland and a settlement could be reached
aimed at breaking a deadlock over guerrilla disarmament in the
province.
</P>
<P>
"There has been huge progress, and there is no doubt about that
whatever," Reuters quoted Blair as saying in Belfast, the capital
of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that we can do it," Blair said of the talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks adjourned until later on Thursday as the British
province's political parties blaming each other for the deadlock.
</P>
<P>
A British spokesman said the talks would resume at noon (1100
GMT) after a marathon overnight session failed to reach a
settlement that would keep the Good Friday peace accord signed
last year alive.
</P>
<P>
The accord's deadline of midnight on Wednesday passed without
the main pro-Irish and pro-British parties reaching any agreement
on guerrilla disarmament.
</P>
<P>
British newspapers reported that Blair is desperate to save
the Good Friday accord from collapse.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein has offered to decommission its military wing, the
Irish Republican Army, by next May, according to The Times
Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
