<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Publishes White Book on NATO Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslavia on Thursday published a
white book on the human life losses and material damages caused by
the 78 days of NATO bombing against the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
The 417-page book, entitled NATO Crimes in Yugoslavia and
published by the Yugoslav foreign ministry, uses 400 pictures,
lots of tables and charts as well as quotes from eyewitnesses to
document the deaths of civilian people and the damages to civilian
facilities in the country during the first month of NATO bombing.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Deputy Foreign Minister Zoran Novakovic said at the
launching ceremony that by publishing the white book the country
hoped that the war crimes committed against peace will never
happen again; the crimes against humanity and civilians will not
be forgotten, and those responsible for the crimes will not be
forgiven.
</P>
<P>
The book starts with the NATO bombing against a civilian convoy
of ethnic Albanians inside the Yugoslav province of Kosovo on
April 14. The record of evidence of NATO bombing against
civilians and civilian facilities continued place by place, from
Cacak, Vranje, Aleksinac, Pristina, Cuprija, Subotica, Batajnica
and Nis to Djakovica, and scores of villages in Kosovo and in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The documentary evidence from March 24 to April 24 also
includes details of human life losses and material damages from
NATO bombing against such civilian facilities as medical
institutions and educational facilities, cultural monuments,
bridges, telecommunications facilities, television transmitters
and relay facilities and oil and oil refinery facilities.
</P>
<P>
Rodoljub Etiwski, a legal advisor from the foreign ministry,
told the press that another white book would soon be published to
give evidence to the NATO bombing between April 24 and June 9.
</P>
<P>
He said that unfortunately not all war crimes committed against
the Balkan country had been documented in the first book. But
later editions of the white book will add more evidence to fully
document the human life losses and material damages inflicted by
the NATO bombing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
