<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Launches Photos Competition on Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) has announced its third International Photographic
Competition on the Environment, aiming at raising global
environmental awareness at the dawn of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
"Maybe it is difficult for some people to write about the
environmental issues, but it is easy for many to take a picture to
express their views," UNEP spokesman Tore Brevik told the press
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Entrants are encouraged to document the state of the world's
environment through their photographs showing their hopes and
fears for the planet and human struggle for sustainable
development, according to Brevik, who is based here in Nairobi,
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Photographs can either focus on the beauty and wonder of our
natural environment, or depict the fragility and damage wrought by
the unbridled development of mankind, said Brevik.
</P>
<P>
"On our difficult journey toward sustainable development, we
need a common language, a language that can instantly touch the
hearts and minds," said Klaus Toepfer, Executive Director of the
UNEP.
</P>
<P>
There are two categories for the competition - Adult and Junior
 Divisions. Gold, Silver and Bronze prizes and Honorary Mention
will be awarded for each division in the U.N. Millenium Conference
to be held in New York in September 2000, said Steve Jackson,
Audio Visual Officer of the UNEP.
</P>
<P>
There will also be special prizes from the UNEP and Canon
company, the sponsor of the competition, a scholarship from the
International Photographic Council as well as a digital camera
special prize, Jackson added.
</P>
<P>
Gold Prize winners in the Adult and Junior Divisions will
receive 20,000 U.S. dollars and 2,000 U.S. dollars respectively,
said Jackson.
</P>
<P>
The first UNEP photographic competition, timed to coincided
with the Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro in 1992, attracted over
30,000 entries from 144 countries.
</P>
<P>
The second competition was held in 1994-1995 to commemorate the
50th Anniversary of the United Nations and received more than
44,000 entries from 153 countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0447 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Begin Freeze on CFCs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- With the completion of the grace
period granted by an international convention, developing
countries are set to begin a freeze on production and consumption
of CFCs with an aim to phase out the substance globally by the
year 2010.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome the continued participation of the developing
countries as we step up our efforts to heal the ozone layer,"
Klaus Toepfer, Executive Director of the United Nations
Environment Program (UNEP), said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Our task is a challenging one, but is is made more manageable
with the total commitment of all parties to the Montreal
Protocol," Toepfer said. "The success of the protocol underscores
the necessity for mutual cooperation in attaining a common goal."
</P>
<P>
The Montreal Protocol on Substances that Deplete the Ozone
Layer was adopted in September 1987.
</P>
<P>
It allowed developing countries a grace period to phase out
their consumption and production of ozone-depleting substances
such as CFCs and halons, in recognition of the fact that they
needed time to obtain funds and introduce alternative
technologies.
</P>
<P>
To ensure compliance with the protocol, a multilateral fund was
set up to help developing countries pay the costs incurred and to
promote the transfer of alternative substances and technologies,
said Gilbert Bankobeza, legal officer in the Ozone Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
Industrialized countries provided financing for the fund which
has so far disbursed about 900 million U.S. dollars to more than
110 developing countries to enable them to phase out more than
half of their consumption of ozone-depleting substances, Bankobeza
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0448 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Election Com. Allowed to Begin National Vote Count </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- After a heated debate among its
members, Indonesia's General Elections Commission (KPU) at its
plenary meeting here Thursday decided to allow the Indonesian
Election Committee (PPI) to begin the national vote count.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made through voting after the KPU members
failed to reach a consensus on the exact date for the national
vote count by the PPI.
</P>
<P>
"The chief of the plenary session has tried to persuade the KPU
members to make the decision through consensus but there was no
agreement among them. That is why we resorted to voting. We must
abide by the rules of game if we want to uphold democracy," KPU
deputy chief Adnan Buyung Nasution said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly before the vote began, 11 KPU members walked out of the
session room in protest of the KPU chief's decision. They wanted
all election violations and discrepancies to be resolved before
the votes are counted.
</P>
<P>
Of the 57 KPU members attending, 54 favored the KPU's decision
to begin the national vote count, 2 opposed it and one abstained.
</P>
<P>
The KPU had originally scheduled the national vote count on
June 21. KPU Chairman Rudini meanwhile said the final vote count
could only begin after all tabulations and other substantial data
are reprocessed.
</P>
<P>
KPU is expected to conclude its final vote count before July 8.
</P>
<P>
The number of votes collected by the KPU as of Thursday
afternoon has reached 64.8 million. The data showed that the
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle (PDI-P) leads with 23.25
million votes, followed by Golkar Party with 12.3 million votes,
National Awakening Party (PKB) with 11.1 million votes, United
Development Party (PPP) with 6.4 million votes and National
Mandate Party (PAN) with 4.4 million votes.
</P>
<P>
According to unofficial results collected by the official
Antara News Agency from the provincial chapters of PPI, until
Thursday afternoon, PDI-P remained in the lead with 34.2 million
votes, Golkar 22.38 million votes, PKB 13.1 million votes, PPP
10.56 million votes and PAN 6.9 million votes.
</P>
<P>
KPU officials stressed that the results of the election will be
determined by the official data issued by the KPU, and other data
are unofficial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
