<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0449 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Leaders Pay Tribute to Zimbabwe's Nkomo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 1 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki and his predecessor Nelson Mandela paid tribute to
Zimbabwean Vice-President Joshua Nkomo (83) who died of prostate
cancer Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a message of condolence to Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe, Mbeki said Nkomo had been an outstanding figure in the
country's liberation struggle and a "leader of Africa".
</P>
<P>
The South African president said he had learned of Nkomo's
death earlier in the day with a deep sense of sadness.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the government and people of South Africa, Mbeki
extended heartfelt condolences to the government and people of
Zimbabwe, and Nkomo's family.
</P>
<P>
"Many among us may not be aware that you, Comrade President,
and Comrade Nkomo bequeathed a legacy of patriotic unity and
cooperation, which has served as an inspiring example to South
Africans.
</P>
<P>
"The importance of this legacy is even more relevant to our
continent today," Mbeki said through his office.
</P>
<P>
Nelson Mandela also sent condolences to the family of Nkomo,
South African Press Association (SAPA) said.
</P>
<P>
Reacting to the news during a visit to Mount Ayliff in the
Eastern Cape, Mandela said: "Well, that is regrettable because he
was one of those freedom fighters who stood up for justice at the
most difficult time in the course of our struggle."
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he knew Nkomo while the late Zimbabwean
vice-president was studying as a social worker in Johannesburg.
"Even then he showed great interest in the living conditions of
our people," said Mandela.
</P>
<P>
Together with Zimbabwean President Mugabe, Nkomo not only
liberated Zimbabwe from the white minority government of Ian
Smith, but also united the country's two main liberation movements
-- the Zimbabwe African People's Union and the Zimbabwe African
National Union.
</P>
<P>
"We sent our deepest condolences to the family and the country
as a whole," said Mandela at a fund-raising function. 
</P>
</TEXT>
