<HEADLINE> Queen Elizabeth Opens Scottish Parliament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Queen Elizabeth II on Thursday
formally opened the Scottish Parliament with a speech praising the
Scots' "wit, determination and humor" and their contributions to
the life of the United Kingdom as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Her address to an array of politicians, celebrities and
citizens in the Scottish Parliament's temporary home at the
Assembly Hall in Edinburgh culminated the day's proceedings.
</P>
<P>
She called the day a "turning point," from which democracy had
been renewed in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The new 129-member parliament was the result of a referendum
held in 1997 with its members voted on May 6, 1999. The previous
parliament voted itself out of existence in the 1707 union with
England to form Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, political leaders delivered speeches in Parliament
Hall, part of the law courts where the Scottish parliament last
sat in 1707.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who has to stay in Belfast
for the Northern Ireland peace talks, did not show up in the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
The Scottish Crown, which dates back to the 15th Century, was
brought to the Assembly Hall and used in a public ceremony for the
first time since 1953.
</P>
<P>
It was placed in front of the Queen in the Assembly Hall's
debating chamber.
</P>
<P>
Guests attending the ceremony included ambassadors from more
than 30 countries and speakers from 13 parliaments.
</P>
<P>
Also present were leading figures from the armed forces,
businesses, churches, the circles of entertainment and sports in
Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The eve of the parliament's birth was marked with several
beacons, lit at strategic locations in the city after sunset, and
hundreds of people staying up all night to celebrate the re-
founding of their parliament after nearly 300 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
