<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctor Devotes His Life To Ethnic Minority People (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese doctor who has worked for
36 years in China's westernmost county has become a national model
for his outstanding service to the mostly ethnic minority people
there.
</P>
<P>
The 59-year-old Dr. Wu Dengyun was born in east China's coastal
province of Jiangsu, but has spent his entire adult life in Wuqia
County in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, where 72 percent
of the people are Khalkhas. He came to Wuqia after graduating from
Yangzhou Medical School in 1963 and is esteemed by the people of
this poverty-stricken county and the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
Because of his resemblance to late Chairman Mao Zedong, the
local people call him a younger brother of Chairman Mao. Public
lectures about his work are being given in major Chinese cities
like Beijing and Shanghai. The doctor is admired not only for his
professionalism, something in great need in a country where
doctors and people in other occupations are often criticized for
their unprofessional or even unethical behavior, but also as a
symbol of harmony and the bond between different ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
There was a lack of blood in the remote mountainous area where
he lives and the local people were afraid of giving blood because
of their belief that blood is where the soul resides. So, over the
years, Wu has donated more than 7 liters of his own blood to save
the lives of his patients.
</P>
<P>
Following his example, his children have also donated blood and
more than 1,000 local government employees have broken the
traditional taboo on blood giving and become donors.
</P>
<P>
Years ago, Wu cut 13 patches of skin off his own body to save
the life of a seriously burned two-year-old Khalkhas boy. In May,
the patient who is now a 29-year-old man, came with his father to
visit the doctor to whom he'll be indebted all his life, but for
whom it is just one of the many acts of help he has given over the
years.
</P>
<P>
"I had to do it," he said simply, "How can you not care when a
person on the brink of death is lying right there in front of your
eyes?"
</P>
<P>
Following in his footsteps, his daughter became a doctor at a
local hospital, but tragedy hit in May, 1997, when she was killed
in a traffic accident while escorting a cancer patient from Urumqi,
the regional capital, back to Wuqia. Dr. Wu had again given a part
of his life to the local people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0457 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
