<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0458 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Doctor Devotes His Life to Ethnic Minority People(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Wuqia, Dr. Wu is a physician, a surgeon, and about any other
kind of specialist you can name, precisely the kind of doctor that
remote, underdeveloped regions need. From the very beginning up to
the end of the 1980s, he spent three or four months of each year
in the countryside helping people.
</P>
<P>
After he was appointed chief surgeon at the county hospital, he
ruled that people from poor families only needed to pay for their
medicines, and those who couldn't afford could delay payment until
they could sell their sheep to the hospital kitchen in the fall,
or do odd jobs around the hospital, to cover expenses.
</P>
<P>
"We make a 100 percent effort if there is 1 percent of hope,"
he said, "and we won't delay treatment because of a money problem,
" --not a small thing at a county hospital in a poverty-stricken
area, where it's hard to get new medical equipment or a new
ambulance. So, he focuses his efforts on training staff recruited
locally to replace Han Chinese doctors who have found jobs
elsewhere and who can't adjust to the harsh climate and
environment.
</P>
<P>
Through a 10-year training program, Dr. Wu has sent 26 Khalkhas
doctors and nurses for professional training in schools and
hospitals in more developed areas and today, 7 out of every 10
staff members are from local ethnic minorities. Where they once
found it difficult just to do an appendectomy, they now can do
just about everything except chest surgery or a craniotomy, making
this a rare hospital for a border area.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Wu grew up in eastern China in mild weather and a milder
environment but the pastureland of the Pamirs has become his home
and the 43,000 people living here his family.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0459 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia, NATO Trying to Iron Out Disputes Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian military officials are
coordinating with NATO on most of the issues relating to Russian
peacekeepers in Kosovo and will hopefully solve remaining issues
in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
Russian military negotiators, led by Vice Admiral Valentin
Kuznetsov in Belgium trying to find a way for a deal with NATO
commanders, have insisted on letting their troops be under the
control of only Russian commanders, and wanted them deployed also
in zones under Italian, French, American and German control in
Kosovo, NATO sources said.
</P>
<P>
Kuznetsov told Itar-Tass on Thursday that the atmosphere during
the three-day talks was friendly and business-like, and both sides
have coordinated most of the issues shown in a protocol.
</P>
<P>
The remaining problems will be ironed out during a second visit
of the delegation to NATO headquarters in Belgium 10 days later,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the chairman of NATO's military Committee, Admiral
Guido Venturony, of Italy, told a press briefing Wednesday that "
only minor problems are left" between NATO and Russia over Kosovo
peacekeeping arrangement.
</P>
<P>
He also told reporters that Kuznetsov and his delegation had
broken off the talks for further instructions from Moscow. They
were not expected back at the military command in Mons, Belgium,
until next week.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said the Russian officers had also asked for a
Russian role in the political supervision of operations by the 3,
600 Russian troops who are expected to go to Kosovo. But NATO
insists on keeping political control of all Kosovo operations in
the hands of the North Atlantic Council, NATO's 19 permanent
representatives at the alliance's headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
