<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Seizes Back Towns From Ethiopians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Somali National Front (SNF)
faction Thursday declared that their forces have once again taken
control of Garbaharrey and Bur Dhubo towns from the Ethiopian
forces who had allegedly captured them three days ago.
</P>
<P>
According to an SNF faction spokesman in Mogadishu, their
forces have launched well-organized and separate attacks on the
newly-established Ethiopian bases in these towns, thus forcing
them to retreat.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Thrahim Jama Howleh, said that the SNF forces
have killed two Ethiopian soldiers and captured another uniformed
one during the ambush on Bur Dhobo town.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that his forces have lost three fighters while 10
others have sustained gun-shot wounds during the attacks for
control of these towns.
</P>
<P>
Howleh said the consecutive attacks especially during the night
time have forced the Ethiopians to withdraw from the regional
capital of Garbaharrey and Bur Dhubo towns later Wednesday night
and early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the SNF forces will pursue the
Ethiopians to the last point as long as they occupy what he called
their territories in Gedo region.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopians are now reportedly stationed in Luq town, the
former Al- Itihad Islam organization stronghold.
</P>
<P>
Howleh further said that the SNF men won't commit to any
cease-fire treaty until they liberate the remaining three towns of
Bulo Hawo, Dolow and Luq which still remain under what he called
the Ethiopian occupation.
</P>
<P>
However, eyewitnesses contacted on the VHF radio in those towns
said Ethiopians have withdrawn from Garbaharrey and Bur Dhubo
towns early Thursday morning on their own accord.
</P>
<P>
The eyewitnesses said that the Ethiopians did not seem to have
been in a hurry and left the area in full confidence of their
forces.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there are unconfirmed reports indicating that the
Ethiopians have agreed with some of the elders of those towns to
keep the area safe and pave the way for reconciliation between the
ethiopian-backed portion of the SNF and its mainstream group led
by General Omar Hajji Masalleh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
