<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jobless Claims Fall Sharply Last Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The number of U.S. new claims
for unemployment benefits dropped unexpectedly last week, the
Labor Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Department reported that 299,000 people filed new claims
for jobless benefits at the week ending June 26 -- down by 5,000
from the previous week.
</P>
<P>
The four-week moving average for claims, which helps smooth out
week-to-week volatility, also was down to 307,000, the lowest
level since May 29 when they were at 305,500.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the low jobless claims applications reflect an
extremely tight labor market, on which the Federal Reserve is
keeping a watchful eye.
</P>
<P>
The Department said that for the week ending June 19, 29 states
and territories reported declined in jobless claims, while 23 had
increases. The state data lag a week behind the national figures.
</P>
</TEXT>
