<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0470 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Construction Spending Falls Second Straight Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department reported
Thursday that construction spending dropped by 0.9 percent in May,
after falling by 2 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
The Department said the declines were widespread, with decreases
reported in single-family homes, apartment buildings, hotels and
motels as well as big government construction projects.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the decrease was not expected and it indicated
one of the U.S. economy's strongest sectors is starting to slow.
</P>
<P>
Home building and other construction activity, driven by low
mortgage rates, were a key contributing factor to the strong
economic growth in the early part of the year. Sales of new and
existing homes had hit record highs during the winter.
</P>
<P>
But the pace of home sales has cooled in recent months, owing
to the rising mortgage rates. Sales of new homes fell 5.1 percent
in May while sales of existing homes dropped 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Department's construction report showed that spending on
residential building fell 0.5 percent in May to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of 320 billion dollars with both
single-family homes and apartments showing declines.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, construction spending for all private building
projects fell 0.7 percent, the second straight month of decline,
something that has not happened for three years. Spending on
factories, hotels and hospitals all saw declines. But spending on
office buildings showed a gain.
</P>
<P>
Also, spending on government construction projects dropped 1.6
percent in May, the third straight monthly decline, the first time
that has happened in eight years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
