<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0471 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Stocks Tumble </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- China's two bourses, in Shanghai
and Shenzhen, saw strong market response to the country's first
securities law, which became effective today.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai composite index closed at 1560.79 points, down 7.
61 percent, while the Shenzhen composite index was down 7.99
percent to end at 466.62 points.
</P>
<P>
Market analysts here say that the drop reflects a wavering in
investor confidence when institutional investors began dumping
stocks after taking profits from the upward trend in recent weeks
and they hint at a possible link with the contrary mood of
investors because of the new law.
</P>
<P>
On the positive side, the securities law will help the long-
term development of China's stock market, but on the negative side,
investors fear that the withdrawing of large amounts of funds
could make it hard for the remaining capital to support the market,
said one analyst.
</P>
<P>
Other analysts link the downward trend to technical
readjustments and to rumors that certain dealers could be punished
for irregularities and that stocks held by legal persons might go
on sale after years of being officially prohibited. There are also
fears that a large number of big companies may go public in the
near future to get a share of the stock market too quickly.
</P>
<P>
Many stock investors here were worried about today's market
drop and said that it has damaged the market's status and that it
will be very costly to mend it if the trend continues, but that
the market could continue to slide down if there is more negative
information and further destroy the confidence of smaller
investors.
</P>
<P>
Last weekend, when large numbers of smaller investors flooded
into local stock outlets across the country to pay sky-high prices,
their big counterparts, the institutional investors, had begun
retreating.
</P>
<P>
Local experts warned that if the downward trend continues, a
large amount of smaller buyers could be trapped.
</P>
<P>
Friday's trading could be crucial to market development, they
say, and if no favorable information comes, the psychological
barrier of 1520 to 1530 points could be crossed on the Shanghai
stock market.
</P>
<P>
China began to issue stocks in the mid-1980s but the shares
could not be traded until the end of 1990, when the Shanghai and
Shenzhen stock exchanges opened.
</P>
<P>
There are some 40 million individual stock investors in China.
The recent rally, or what it referred to here as an "eruption",
began on May 19 after two years of sluggish markets.
</P>
<P>
In Beijing, the number of new accounts opened by investors was
said to have approached 20,000 per day last week, up from a few
hundred before the recent bull market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0472 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Net Foreign Debt Rises 28 Percent in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Net foreign debt of the United
States jumped 28 percent in 1998, as foreigners plowed ever more
into U.S. plants, offices, stocks and bonds, and Americans
borrowed more abroad for business investment and consumer
spending, according to the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
The net U.S. international investment position -- the gap
between what foreigners have invested in the United States and
what Americans have invested abroad -- ballooned to 1.24 trillion
U.S. dollars at the end of 1998 from 968 billion dollars a year
earlier. The total is based on the current cost of replacing
factories, equipment and other tangible assets.
</P>
<P>
U.S. assests abroad, at current cost, increased to 4.9 trillion
dollars at the end of 1998 from 4.5 trillion dollars a year
earlier. Foreign assets in the United States rose to 6.2 trillion
dollars from 5.5 trillion dollars during the same period, in large
part reflecting the rising value of U.S. stocks.
</P>
<P>
In the near term, the net inflow of funds benefits the U.S.
economy by providing jobs, capital for businesses, credit for
consumers and helping to keep U.S. interest rates low, economists
say.
</P>
<P>
But they also worry that foreign investors eventually will want
to take their earnings home, and that will mean Americans have to
export more or import less -- in other words, reverse the trade
deficit -- to finance repayments.
</P>
<P>
"The concern is the longer-term one that you build up a large
level of foreign debt. If history is any guide, it could become a
sufficient large share of your economy... that it could raise some
sustainability questions in the minds of the market," Fred
Bergsten, director of the Institute for International Economics,
was quoted by the Wall Street Journal on Thursday as saying.
</P>
<P>
If investment is measured on a current-cost basis, the United
States went from net creditor to net debtor between 1985 and 1986,
just as the federal government was boosting its borrowing to cover
budget deficits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
