<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, July 1 (Xinhua) -- With the help of the United Nations
High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), Albania began to
repatriate Kosovo refugees on Thursday, according to a report by
the Albanian Telegraphic Agency (ATA).
</P>
<P>
Some 500 Kosovars have arrived at a railway station in Kukes,
northern Albania, ready to go home, ATA said. The UNHCR has set up
two centers in Kukes to distribute food to the departing Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a NATO press center in Albania said that NATO forces
in Albania (AFOR) will work around-the-clock to help repatriate
Kosovo refugees. AFOR will protect the refugees during their trip
home, providing help and medical assistance and coordinating road
traffic, the press center said.
</P>
<P>
Individual Kosovars continued leaving Albania on Thursday. ATA
said that 2,456 people left on their own for Kosovo on the day.
</P>
<P>
ATA also said that 279,000 Kosovars have left for home since
June 13, with about 170,000 more remaining in Albania. 
