<HEADLINE> Air Strike Against Yugoslavia Costs France Billions of Francs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 1 (Xinhua) -- France spent 1.33 billion francs (
about 210 million U.S. dollars) during NATO's air campaign against
Yugoslavia from March 24 till June 10, said a French Parliament
report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report, presented by parliament deputy Jean-Michel
Boucheron, who is in charge of reporting defense spending to the
National Assembly, put the costs of French participation in the
Kosovo Peacekeeping Force (KFOR) this year at 966 million francs (
153 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
French air force dropped 988 bombs, including laser-guided
missiles, on Yugoslav targets, which cost a total of 384 million
francs (60 million dollars), said the report.
</P>
<P>
The latest figures of war costs in Yugoslavia are lower than
predicted by French Defense Minister Alain Richard at the
beginning of June, when the war had not ended.
</P>
<P>
Richard estimated then the war costs for the whole 1999 would
run to between 3.5 billion to 4 billion francs (570 million to 620
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
