<HEADLINE> Solar Energy Fair Held in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 1 (Xinhua) -- A three-day "Solar Energy '99" fair
opened Thursday in Germany's capital city of Berlin, aiming to
further expand the production and utilization of solar power.
</P>
<P>
According to organizers, the sector grows at 20 percent
annually, with 120 megawatts of installed solar power being added
each year around the world. Germany accounts for 10 MW of that
amount.
</P>
<P>
Gernot Oswald, chairman of the Siemens Solar company, praised
the German government's "100,000 rooftops" program to promote the
use of solar panels, saying the program was off to an outstanding
start.
</P>
<P>
"If the program is carried out as foreseen, the German
photovoltaic market will grow by more than 40 percent annually for
the next six years and will increase tenfold the installed
capacity of solar cells in Germany," he said.
</P>
<P>
Deutsche Shell executive Fritz Vahrenholt said that if Germany
is to tangibly reduce its carbon dioxide emissions, 30 percent to
50 percent of its primary energy will have to come from renewable
fuel resources by the year 2050, adding that his company aims to
become the market leader in Germany's solar power business.
</P>
<P>
With an annual output of 25 MW, a new solar cell production
facility to be set up in Gelsenkirchen will be the largest of its
kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
British Petroleum executive Peter Knoedel announced that its
subsidiary BP Solar, in taking over the American firm Solarex,
aims to double its share of the world photovoltaic cell market to
20 percent. BP Solar's annual photovoltaic cell production now
comes to 30 MW, he said.
</P>
<P>
Fair organizer Rainer Heinzel predicted that some 20,000 people
will visit the three-day show, adding that next year the fair will
involve other forms of renewable energy resources, such as wind
power, fuel cells and biogas fuels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
