<HEADLINE> ASEAN Energy Ministers to Meet for Power Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Energy ministers from the
Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will meet here
Saturday to discuss a proposed project to install a power grid
network linking all 10 members of the group, Thai News Agency
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They will talk over efforts and ways to complete the project by
the year 2020, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The project was first proposed in 1982, but only limited
progress had been made due to low growth in demand for electricity
in the region, and the situation had worsened since the finance
crisis struck the region two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Massive costs of the project to construct transmission lines
and submarine cables over long distances to suit the complicated
landforms in the region have also made it difficult to find firm
supporters so far, said the report.
</P>
<P>
However, the European Union is reportedly preparing to extend a
new package of loans to support the regional project, which also
requires well-planned regulatory and technical framework.
</P>
<P>
More progress is expected to be made at the upcoming meeting,
including proposed ways to tackle the obstacles.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Thailand, Singapore and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
