<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Becker out, Sampras through at Wimbledon Tennis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Boris Becker of Germany, the
youngest men's champion in Wimbledon history, said goodbye to
centre court on Wednesday after a 6-3, 6-2, 6-3 fourth-round
defeat by second seed Patrick Rafter of Australia.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old veteran was too slow to match big-serving
Rafter's quick game.
</P>
<P>
Rafter plays eighth seed Todd Martin who eased past last year's
finalist Goran Ivanisevic 7-6 6-3 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Pete Sampras of the United States continued his cruise
towards a sixth final in seven years when he beat Daniel Nestor of
Canada 6-3, 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
In the quarter-finals, Sampras meets seventh seed Mark
Philippoussis of Australia who beat another Briton Greg Rusedski 2-
6, 7-6, 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Tim Henman delighted home fans when he saved three
match points on the way to beating former world number one Jim
Courier of the United States 4-6, 7-5, 7-5, 6-7, 9-7.
</P>
<P>
Henman's next opponent is France's Cedric Pioline, who beat
Karol Kucera of Slovakia, the 13th seed, 6-4, 5-7, 7-6, 4-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
In the women's event, second seed Steffi Graf of Germany
finished off Belgium's teenage qualifier Kim Clijsters in eight
minutes to win their rain-delayed match 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Graf plays sixth seed Venus Williams in the quarter-finals
following the powerful American's 3-6, 6-3, 6-2 win over Russian
Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
A woman qualifier will reach the semifinals at Wimbledon for
the first time after American Alexandra Stevenson came from a set
and a matchpoint down to beat compatriot Lisa Raymond 2-6, 7-6, 6-
1.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old now plays Jelena Dokic, the 16-year-old
Australian who beat top seed Martina Hingis in the first round.
</P>
</TEXT>
