<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0490 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Calls International Conference on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan convened an international conference Wednesday to accelerate
the deployment of troops and U.N. personnel in the war-torn
Yugoslav province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Annan said a day earlier that he would call on the 18 nations
and three international organizations attending the meeting to
offer personnel and resources in order that the U.N. civilian
operations in Kosovo work efficiently.
</P>
<P>
Upon his arrival at the U.N. headquarters early Wednesday,
Annan told reporters, "As you know, we do have a major
responsibility in Kosovo."
</P>
<P>
"I think it is important to bring the ministers together to
discuss what our needs are, to try and accelerate the deployment,
particularly of the troops, and the money we need to get the job
done, and also to bring them up to date as to what the situation
is on the ground and how things are going," he said.
</P>
<P>
Attending the four-hour meeting are the foreign ministers of
Belgium, Britain, Finland, France, Germany, Greece, Italy, the
Netherlands, Spain, Turkey and the United States, which are
described as "friends of the Secretary-General for Kosovo." The
other seven nations represented are Austria, Canada, China,
Denmark, Japan, Russia and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
Shen Guofang, China's acting permanent representative to the
United Nations, attended the meeting as the senior representative
of Chinese Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from the European Union, which is charged with the
reconstruction of Kosovo, and the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, responsible for institution building, as
well as the Organization of the Islamic Conference have also been
invited to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo's most pressing need at the moment is an international
police force which can tackle the rising crime in the region with
the withdrawal of Serbian police and military forces and the
return of more than 300,000 ethnic Albanian refugees. So far, only
a small U.N. contingent has arrived from the international mission
in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Police seconded to the United Nations are in shorter supply
than soldiers, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said Tuesday. "There
are no police barracks on our front lawn."
</P>
<P>
So far some 18 countries have promised to send 900 police
forces, who are expected to begin moving into Kosovo next month in
contingents of 150-200, Eckhard said. They come from Austria,
Bangladesh, Bulgaria, Canada, Denmark, Egypt, Italy, Kenya,
Lithuania, Malaysia, Nepal, Pakistan, Romania, Tanzania, Turkey,
Britain, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Annan is expected to announce who will be his special
representative or chief administrator for the entire operation,
now run temporarily by Sergio de Mello, the Brazilian U.N.
undersecretary-general for humanitarian affairs. He has said he
would nominate a European for the position.
</P>
<P>
Another portfolio has also been added to the existing list: a
deputy special representative for the U.N. mission in Kosovo,
known as UNMIK. "The deputy is to coordinate the four pillars of
the U.N. mission," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Both Britain and France are vying for the post and some U.N.
officials prefer Martti Ahtisaari, whose tenure of office as the
Finnish president has another six months to finish.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, which has been getting
tents and supplies to returning Kosovo refugees, says it has only
2.4 million U.S. dollars left for July. It estimated that up to 45,
000 houses in Kosovo need to be repaired or rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard noted that the U.N. mission will carry out its mandate
without undermining the sovereignty and territorial integrity of
the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia, as stipulated by the June 10
Security Council resolution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0491 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Non-Confidence Motion on Kenyan Vice-President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Vice-President George
Saitoti survived the non-confidence motion initiated by a
parliament member of the opposition party in the National Assembly
here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The motion was introduced by Otieno Kajwang, claiming to be a
move to root out corrupt individuals in the east African country.
</P>
<P>
As the ruling party dominates the parliament, the motion was
seen by local analysts just as an attack on Saitoti.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that the motion aroused debate among the
parliament members.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti was appointed vice-president in 1989 and the position
was left vacant following the 1997 general election and was
re-appointed by President Daniel arap Moi earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
He was Finance Minister from 1983 to 1992 when nearly 100
million U.S. dollars was drained from the treasury as the
government gave the Goldberg International tax and duty breaks and
allowed the company sole rights to export gold and diamond. It is
known as the Goldberg scandal.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Kenya's economy is sluggish with each passing
year. The economic growth rate in 1998 registered only 1.8
percent as against 2.3 percent in 1997 and 4.6 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown economy in the country is attributed to many
reasons such as natural disasters, poor governance and
infrastructures, reduced foreign investment and graft among
government officials.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund suspended a 205-million-U.S.
dollar loan to Kenya in July 1997 allegedly because of the
country's poor governance and corruption, which had worsened
Kenya's economic development.
</P>
<P>
The Goldberg case is now still under court proceedings. The
conclusion of this case is one of the conditions the IMF has
imposed on the Kenyan government before it resumes the talks on
aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
