<HEADLINE> Canadian Minister Lashes at U.S. Protectionism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Canadian Trade Minister Sergio
Marchi is warning of challenges raised by a protectionist U.S.
Congress and a shift of economic power to the south and west of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
"You have a very protectionist, inward-looking Congress," the
minister said Tuesday, emerging from the middle of a two-day
cabinet session.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out a "very dangerous attitude for congressmen to
take...a very harmful position for the international community."
</P>
<P>
The minister also noted that economic power has been shifting
within the United States from the north and northeast to the south
and southwest, away from the Canadian border and long-standing
Canadian commercial ties.
</P>
<P>
"What that means is we've got to get to know a whole part of
the United States," the minister declared, adding "we have to take
a look at a whole new north-south axis from the one that we've
been traditionally used to."
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's cabinet session was described by the local media as "
concentrated on Canada-U.S. issues," especially recurring disputes
over Canadian softwood lumber and agricultural exports.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Jean Chretien expressed an idea of a hemisphere-
wide Free Trade Agreement of the Americas at the beginning of the
cabinet session. Despite a warm relationship between Chretien and
U.S. President Bill Clinton, the pan-America free trade idea has
met a lukewarm reception in Washington, according to reports of
the Canadian media. 
</P>
</TEXT>
