<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for More Efforts on Population, Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said on Wednesday that progress has been made in recent
years in meeting the challenge of population and development, but
there is a lot of jobs to do.
</P>
<P>
Opening a special session of the General Assembly on the follow
up to the Cairo conference on population and development in 1994,
Annan gave some examples of how things have changed since the
first population conference 25 years ago:
</P>
<P>
-- Women in developing countries have fewer than three children
instead of an average of five then,
</P>
<P>
-- Sixty percent of couples use family planning and the vast
majority of governments support it, in contrast to the fact that
only thirty percent of couples used it then,
</P>
<P>
-- In many countries fewer women die in childbirth.
</P>
<P>
-- Growth of world population has slowed from 2-% to 1.3%.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the international community should do more, as
</P>
<P>
-- In too many countries, girls still do not have the same
chance to be educated as boys,
</P>
<P>
-- Too many women still cannot choose when or whether to become
pregnant,
</P>
<P>
-- Too many women are victims of sexual violence especially
during conflict,
</P>
<P>
-- Too many people are exposed to sexually transmitted diseases
and AIDS,
</P>
<P>
-- People in developing countries still die too young.
</P>
<P>
Annan said since the Cairo conference, developing countries
have proved their commitment, but they are "cruelly limited in
what they can achieve without outside help".
</P>
<P>
"They are entitled to expect more sympathy, and better
treatment, from countries which are more fortunate," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0499 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO: Many Drugs Donated to Albania Useless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Vast amounts of drugs donated in
humanitarian aid to Albania in May are useless, the World Health
Organization (WHO) said here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to a WHO report, 400,000 tablets and 1,200 large-
volume intravenous fluids have passed their expiry date and 2
million tablets, 8,500 vials for injection and 16,000 tubes of
cream for external use will become useless by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
"There is no way they can be distributed and used before the
end of the year," said Indro Mattei, a member of the Swiss
Disaster Relief Unit under the WHO Humanitarian Assistance Project
Office in Tirana.
</P>
<P>
"We estimate that 50 percent of the drugs coming into Albania
donated by non-medical organizations are inappropriate or useless
and will have to be destroyed."
</P>
<P>
"We are very concerned that some pharmaceutical companies are
using this humanitarian crisis to get rid of unwanted stockpiles,"
Mattei added.
</P>
<P>
An analysis of import permit documents submitted to the
Albanian Ministry of Health by humanitarian agencies in May showed
that 65 percent of the drugs presented an inadequate expiry date,
32 percent were declared with brand names that are unfamiliar to
Albanian health professionals, and almost 10 percent of medical
donations were not accompanied by any detailed packing list at all,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
It said that the situation in June had not improved.
</P>
<P>
In April 1999, the Albanian health authorities softened import
controls to speed up the entry of badly-needed drugs to meet the
demands of the 460,000 Kosovar refugees.
</P>
<P>
WHO also stressed that good coordination of drug donations will
be crucial to avoid duplication, waste and the arrival of
unnecessary and inappropriate drugs. The U.N. agency urged strict
adherence to international guidelines for drug donations worked
out by WHO with major humanitarian agencies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0500 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
