<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0507 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Opposition Voices Concern over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 30 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's opposition
parties Wednesday expressed concern over the government's decision
to send troops to the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) as
peace-keepers.
</P>
<P>
While generally acknowledging that South Africa has a role to
play in maintaining peace in the continent, the parties warned
that it should not send troops until there is a clear peace
agreement accepted by all parties.
</P>
<P>
South African President Thabo Mbeki told parliament earlier
Wednesday that South African troops would be sent to the DRC as
peace-keepers once a cease-fire is in place.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party (DP), South Africa's biggest opposition
party, said that it neither condemned nor supported the decision
to send peace-keepers to the DRC.
</P>
<P>
But it said the government had to be certain there is a peace
agreement accepted by all parties before sending in its troops.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from countries involved in the DRC conflict have been
meeting in Zambian capital Lusaka in the past few days to try to
put an end to the 11-month war.
</P>
<P>
The talks have given hopes for a possible cease-fire in the
vast central African country. But the ministers from various
countries concerned have so far not been able to reach agreement
to the draft cease-fire document.
</P>
<P>
Freedom Front (FF) leader Constand Viljoen, a former head of
the South African defense force, said he is opposed to the
decision, because the South African troops are not well trained or
disciplined enough for such kind of mission.
</P>
<P>
"Discipline is of absolute importance, as the troops have to be
 completely neutral," Viljoen said.
</P>
<P>
He also questioned who would pay for the peace-keeping
operation, noting that the burden would likely fall on South
African tax payers.
</P>
<P>
However, the New National Party (NNP) and the United Democratic
 Movement (UDM) supported the decision, saying South Africa could
not escape its peace-keeping responsibilities in Africa.
</P>
<P>
UDM leader Bantu Holomisa said sending in peace-keepers would
be in line with a decision by the United Nations and the
Organization of African Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
"It is felt that we should participate," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, analysts said that a U.N. approval was essential for
any peace-keeping force to be sent to the DRC, especially when
considering the huge cost of such an exercise.
</P>
<P>
Director of the Institute for Security Studies Jakki Cilliers
said it is vital for South Africa and Africa as a whole that any
peace-keeping force be properly mandated by U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Cilliers said that the United States -- U.N.'s biggest debtor
-- appears keen that those who participate should pay the costs,
and it is unlikely that the United States would participate in the
DRC mission.
</P>
<P>
Another problem is that the U.N. was planning to provide a
peace-keeping force of no more than 30,000 people for the DRC,
Cilliers said.
</P>
<P>
Although this is large by international standards, it is
hopelessly inadequate for the DRC -- a country the size of a
quarter of Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
South African Defense Department said Wednesday that it could
take considerable time to finalize details for the deployment of
South African troops in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Patrick Lekota said South African troops would
be part of a "non-combative" monitoring mission, the size of which
would be decided by the OAU. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
