<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-30 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Tough Road to Negotiation Table in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- There is a rough road to go before
the two rival sides in Cyprus sit again on the negotiation talbe
though the U.N. Security Council on Tuesday urged them to resume
talks in autumn on reuniting Cyprus, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots have already rejected a talks resumption
call proposed recently by the seven most industrialized nations
and Russia, or G-8, and echoed in a report by Annan.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued on June 20 at the end of their annual
summit in Cologne, Germany, the leaders of G-8 urged the Greek and
Turkish Cypriots to enter talks without setting any pre-conditions
and negotiate in good faith until a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council on Tuesday passed two resolutions,
which clarified the parameters for a Cyprus settlement, and called
on the two sides to hold unconditional talks by putting all issues
on the table.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots have been entrenched in a position that
they will return to the negotiation table only as their
self-declared state in the northern third of the island is
recognized and the negotiation is for a confederation.
</P>
<P>
They said that bi-communal talks, which have dragged on for
decades, do not reflect realities on the island and any future
negotiations must be on a state-to-state basis.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriots declared in 1983 the Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus, which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal federation formula, but the peace talks were
stalled in 1997 after Turkish Cypriots decided to stay out of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Cypriot side in 1998 conditioned the resumption of
the talks on the establishment of a confederation on the island
and the incoming talks should be held between two equal states.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash said he would not attend
any talks at which President Glafcos Clerides represented the
Cyprus government. Denktash argued that Clerides represents only
part of the island.
</P>
<P>
"They say the talks should be without preconditions. But you
put the precondition that a government of Cyprus exists, which is
why there has been no settlement in Cyprus," Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
Backing Denktash, Suleyman Demirel, the Turkish president, has
also reiterated that "the existence of two sovereign states must
be accepted," warning that a forced solution in Cyprus will create
a clash between Turkey and Greece, the ally of the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Cypriots have said they are willing to engage in
talks without preconditions, but have flatly rejected the
confederation solution for the island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides said he will refuse to discuss confederation if the
issue is brought up at negotiations with the Turkish Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
There are obvious concerns among Greek Cypriot politicians
that the phraseology in U.N. resolutions - "put all issues on the
table" - may open the door for the Turkish side to table demands
for confederation and recognition of two states.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0511 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Gives Priority to Cairo Program of Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- China has made the
population issue a strategic one and integrated it into the
overall program for socio-economic development, its representative
told a special session of U.N. General Assembly on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Since the Cairo Conference on population and development in
1994, China has given high priority to the implementation of the
Program of Action, said Wang Zhongyu, State Councillor and
Secretary-General of the State Council.
</P>
<P>
China, the most populous developing country in the world,
formulated the National Family Planning Program and set long-term
goals for its population and family planning work, he said.
</P>
<P>
While opposed to the use of coercive measures, China's
population program puts more emphasis on the integrated approach
of carrying out publicity and education campaigns, providing
quality services in reproductive health and family planning and
bringing into play the role of the civil society and NGOs, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Special attention has been given to combining the family
planning program in the rural areas with economic development,
poverty-alleviation, universal education programs and improvement
of women's status, Wang added.
</P>
<P>
He said China's family planning program has not only stabilized
its population and promoted its social-economic development, but
also greatly contributed to the stabilization of the world
population.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, China is still faced with grave challenges in
the field of population and development.
</P>
<P>
The annual increase of about 12 million people to its
population exerts a great pressure upon its social-economic
development, resource utilization, environmental protection,
education, medical care and creates many new problems.
</P>
<P>
Turning to international cooperation for meeting the challenge
of population and development, Wang said China would call on the
developed nations to honor their commitment and provide financial
assistance to developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
