<HEADLINE> Russian Troops to Transit Through Greek Ports for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Russia is expected to begin
transiting its troops and heavy equipment through Greek ports for
the Yugoslav province of Kosovo next week.
</P>
<P>
Russia had approached Greece to allow troops to transit through
the Greek ports as part of the NATO-led peacekeeping force in
Kosovo and talks between the two countries over the matter were
nearing an end, the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) quoted
a Greek military source as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the only issue still to be tackled was
whether Thessaloniki, Litohoro or Volos would be used as their
transit points.
</P>
<P>
There was a possibility that all the three ports would be used
and Russian military officials might be in the northern Greek port
of Thessaloniki as early as Thursday to prepare for the
transports, the source added.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of the Kosovo crisis, Thessaloniki has been
a major transit point for NATO troops heading for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 14,000 soldiers and 7,000 vehicles have
passed through the port. 
</P>
</TEXT>
