<HEADLINE> U.S. Leading Economic Index Rebounds in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. leading economic
indicators rose 0.3 percent in May, more than reversing the 0.1
percent decline in April, the Conference Board, a prominent
research group, reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report said with the increase of 0.3 percent in May, the
leading index stands at 107.4. During the six-month span through
May, the leading index rose 1.1 percent, it added.
</P>
<P>
"The leading indicators show the resilience and robustness of
this expansion, which is poised to become the longest ever in
early 2000," said Michael Boldin, Director of Business Cycle
Research at the Conference Board. The index of Leading Economic
Indicators spots economic growth trends for the coming three to
six months.
</P>
<P>
The report said nine of the ten indicators that make up the
leading index rose in May. The most significant increases are
vendor performance, interest rate spread, and money supply in 1992
dollars, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
