<HEADLINE> Arab League Calls for Reconciliation in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League (AL) on Wednesday
called on Somali factions to honor signed agreements in a bid to
seek national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with David Steven, U.N.
chief's representative for the Somali affairs, AL Assistant
Secretary General Ahmed Bin Helly urged the Somali factions to
cooperate with the world community in attaining the goal.
</P>
<P>
The Somali warring factions signed an agreement last year on
establishing a broad-based central government, a move viewed as a
major breakthrough in the war-devastated country. But deep rifts
among the factions have blocked the implementation of the deal.
</P>
<P>
The concerned parties, especially the Arab League and the U.N.,
have been exerting efforts to help the country in the Horn of
Africa end division caused by the civil war since 1991 and realize
peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
Bin Helly said the 22-nation pan-Arab forum has been working
with all parties to help Somalia form a national authority that
will restore the country's position in the Arab world, Africa and
international community. Somalia's AL membership has been frozen
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
He called on AL members to offer technical, financial and
humanitarian aids to the Somali factions that take serious steps
towards national reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the league's readiness to host a reconciliation
conference grouping all the Somali factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
