<HEADLINE> Conservation, Development Urged in Mozambique </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican Prime Minister Pascoal
Mocumbi Wednesday called upon people of all walks of life and
investors at home and abroad to take an active part in the
conservation, recovery and development of the Mozambique Island.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister made the call in capital Maputo at the
opening of an international conference on the comprehensive
conservation and human and economic sustainable development for
the island.
</P>
<P>
Mocumbi asked the participants to make the meeting an impetus
for the overall development of the island and a driving force to
accelerate the development of the whole country.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique Island lies in northern coast and belongs to the
province of Nampula. The three-square-km island is one of the most
ancient cities in the southern African country. It had been the
capital of Mozambique for quite a long time.
</P>
<P>
With many cultural and historic relics, the island was
identified as a human heritage site in 1991 by the U.N.
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization.
</P>
<P>
The island, with a population of 18,000, is facing various
difficulties in the conservation of the relics and the improvement
of people's living because of its worn-out infrastructures.
</P>
<P>
The recovery and development plan for the island includes some
50 projects covering road, water supply, transport,
communications, tourism, fishery and power supply. These projects
will need a total amount of 40 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Development Program (UNDP) country representative in
Maputo, Emmanuel de Casterle, said at the opening that the UNDP
will respond positively to any reasonable requests made by the
Mozambican government.
</P>
<P>
However, he saide that the support and participation of the
civil society, the private sector in particular, is crucial to the
success of the plan.
</P>
<P>
President of the City Council of the Mozambique Island, Abacar
Haimo, said at a fund raising meeting that the residents on the
island cherish great hope for the comprehensive conservation and
sustainable development of their land.
</P>
<P>
Haimo hoped that the meeting will do something for poverty
reduction, job creation, and improved conditions in education,
environment and health care.
</P>
<P>
It was told that a number of countries have expressed their
interest in the plan.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are 140 representatives from the
Mozambican government, U.N. branches, some non-governmental
organizations, as well as such countries as Portugal, Germany,
Canada, Brazil, Egypt and France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
