<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Hopeful Of Congo(K) Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Major differences in the draft
cease-fire agreement for peace in the Democratic Republic of Congo
(DRC) had been ironed out, Zimbabwean Foreign Minister Stan
Mudenge and Defence Minister Moven Mahachi said in Zambian capital
Lusaka Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Contrary to recent press reports that progress was slow and
that hopes of concluding the document were dim, Mudenge and
Mahachi said the atmosphere at the talks was positive and that all
the ministers attending were committed to ending the 11-month war
in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
"The talks have gone well so far, we have reduced the areas of
contention, they are only a few items left in the document," the
Zimbabwe News Agency quoted Mudenge as saying.
</P>
<P>
"It is our objective to complete today, but they are certain
areas centered around definitions which we will look at later," he
said. "There is steady progress and we remain hopeful."
</P>
<P>
"The disagreement is not on the question of peace," Mahachi
said. "People here are concerned that there should be peace in the
DRC. We have agreed in principle that there should be peace."
</P>
<P>
The ministerial meeting started Tuesday and it ended around
2:00 a.m. local time. The talks resumed Wednesday and by 4:00 p.m.
the ministers were continuing with the talks.
</P>
<P>
Defense and Foreign Ministers from the 14 Southern African
Development Community (SADC) member states plus Kenya, Uganda and
Rwanda are attending the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Regional heads of state have been kept on stand-by for a summit
in Lusaka to sign the cease-fire document.
</P>
<P>
Both Mahachi and Mudenge could not specify when the summit
might be held.
</P>
<P>
"We are working on the paragraphing, wording and emphasis and
also on the modalities of implementing the cease-fire agreement
and timetable of implementation," said Mahachi.
</P>
<P>
On the rebel insistence that all foreign forces withdraw
simultaneously, Mahachi and Mudenge said they were currently
working out a timetable for withdrawing the SADC allied forces.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the issue of an integrated national army, Mahachi
said the Congolese had not indicated any problems regarding that.
</P>
<P>
He said the DRC government and rebels would work out how the
armies should be integrated.
</P>
<P>
Mahachi said the division within the rebel movement would not
derail the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
