<HEADLINE> Obasanjo Charges His Team on National Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo
 Wednesday swore in 45 of the 47 ministers cleared by the
country's senate and charged them to help plug the loopholes
through which national resources have been pilfered over the
years.
</P>
<P>
"You have a responsibility to plug the loopholes for the
bending of rules and pilfering of state resources," he told the
ministers, a day after the last set of five nominees were cleared
by the 109-member Senate.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, repeatedly pledging to focus on anti-corruption since
he took over from military regime in May 29, urged the ministers
to join him in the process of national restoration through the
revival of the country's national institutions, battered by years
of military mis-rule.
</P>
<P>
"The great challenge that face the country calls for attention
on the battered economy, the consequences of past mismanagement,"
the president said a week after submitting an anti-corruption
bill to the National Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He said the consequences of years of mismanagement included the
" widening of the poverty gap, the prevalence of hunger and
disease, the deterioration of public service, low capacity
utilization, low agricultural productivity and outmoded
communication."
</P>
<P>
Demanding them to reflect the best "ideals of democratic
governance" in their performance, Obasanjo said that should not
allow the return of the " dark days of deprivation and misery".
</P>
<P>
He urged them to be prepared for public scrutiny and criticism,
saying they should demonstrate a tolerant spirit.
</P>
<P>
As have been speculated, former chief of army staff, Gen.
Theophilus Danjuma was named in charge of the defense portfolio
while Adamu Ciroma, former central bank governor and minister of
Agriculture was named in charge of the Finance Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The surprise portfolio was that of Sule Lamido, secretary of
the defunct social democratic party, who was named the new
Foreign Minister while Tony Anenih, former chairman of the same
party was named for the Works Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The only absentee at the swearing-in was Senator Udo Udoma,
minister of state for the environment, who was rumored to have
rejected the position.  
</P>
