<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Kosovo Mission Faces Big Challenges, Annan Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday said that the U.N. Interim Civilian Mission in
Kosovo (UNMIK) is facing a task which "is enormous in scope and
complex in execution."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief made the statement as he opened an international
conference here on Kosovo, described as "the Friends of the
Secretary-General for Kosovo," which involved foreign minister or
senior representatives from 18 countries.
</P>
<P>
"The mission faces a number of immediate challenges," Annan
said, "The first is coping with the massive daily flow of
returning refugees and internally displaced persons -- at a rate
that exceeds any on record."
</P>
<P>
The humanitarian agencies, led by the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees (UNHCR), "are performing heroically under exceedingly
difficult conditions; they deserve our commendation and support."
</P>
<P>
"The next challenge concerns the establishment of a regime of
law and order," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Only KFOR (the international peacekeepers in Kosovo) has the
capacity to establish a secure environment in Kosovo," he said.
"The demilitarization of armed Kosovar groups is a critical step,
and we are pleased to note that the KLA (the Kosovo Liberation
Army) has complied with the first key deadline set in its
agreement with KFOR."
</P>
<P>
"A third immediate challenge is political in nature," Annan
said, "The UNMIK team in Kosovo, again with KFOR at its side, has
begun to engage the various political groupings in Kosovo, in a
process of rehabilitation and reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
"The long-term success of our mission is defined in terms of
enabling all Kosovars to participate fully and effectively in the
public life of their province: creating viable legislative and
judicial bodies, delivering public services, and establishing a
robust civil society," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Once that is achieved, UNMIK can be drawn down and phased out,
and its activities turned over to indigenous institutions," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"As an interim measure, we have established a United Nations
Trust Fund to finance salaries of local administrators, equipment
to support their work, and quick-hit projects that will
immediately improve the daily lives of Kosovars," he said. "I
urge you to contribute to the fund."
</P>
<P>
Under the Security Council resolution, adopted on June 10,
the U.N. dispatched a civilian mission to Kosovo in parallel
with KFOR.
</P>
<P>
"This civilian presence is intended to provide an interim
administration under which the people of Kosovo are able to enjoy
substantial autonomy," he said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who chaired the four-hour meeting, was asking attending
countries for money and personnel to run the war-torn Yugoslav
province.
</P>
<P>
The pressing issue is the deployment of troops and the short
supply of police in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
