<HEADLINE> Turkish Cypriot Leader Rejects U.N. Call for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash Wednesday rejected a U.N. call for the resumption of the
Cyprus talks in the autumn of this year with no preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Denktash said that "if U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
invites me for exchange of views, I am ready to talk with
him. But there is no ground for talks between me and (Cyprus
President Glafcos) Klerides," according to a report of Anatolia
News Agency reaching here.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously approved resolution Tuesday, the U.N.
Security Council urged Annan to invite the Turkish and Greek
Cypriot sides to resume talks.
</P>
<P>
According to the resolution, the talks should start with no
preconditions, all aspects of the conflict be on the table and the
negotiations last until a settlement is reached.
</P>
<P>
"I will not comment on the other points of the resolution
because we categorically reject it. If they continue to recognize
Greek Cyprus as the government of the whole Cyprus and stick to
its positions despite all our objections, then nothing they say is
binding for us, " Denktash said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. resolution followed a similar appeal by the G-8
countries, grouping the United States, Canada, Britain, France,
Italy, Germany, Japan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the G-8 urged Annan "to invite the leaders of
the two parties on Cyprus to negotiations in the fall of 1999."
</P>
<P>
With Turkey's strong support behind him, Denktash has ruled out
any possibilites of talks not on a state-to-state basis, demanding
an international acknowledgment for the "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that a solution on Cyprus can be reached only with
the recognition of two states, two peoples and two sovereignties.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-dominated
south and the Turkish Cypriots-controlled north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
In 1983, Denktash declared the breakaway "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus," which is now recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunite the island
through a bi-communal federation formula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
