<HEADLINE> EU Accuses FIA of Violating Competition Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 30 (Xinhua) -- European Commission said here
Wednesday that it considers the Federation of International
Automobile (FIA) to be abusing its dominant position and
restricting competition.
</P>
<P>
The European Union (EU) executive body said it has concluded a
thorough investigation, prompted by a number of complaints, into
the way international motor sports is organized and commercially
exploited.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission formally accused the FIA, the body in
charge of international motor racing, of violating the EU
competition law while sending the same statement of objections to
two companies: Formula One Administration Ltd (FOA), which sells
the television rights to the Formula One cchampionship, and
International Sportsworld Communicators (ISC), which markets the
broadcasting rights to a number of major international motor
sports events.
</P>
<P>
A statement of objections is a preliminary procedural document
and not the commission's final verdict on the case. Under the
statement, one of the EU executive body's most significant
conclusions is that many of the contracts concerning the
commercial exploitation of international motor sports,
particularly those involving broadcasters, were viewed on the
basis of a situation unlawful under European Union competition
law.
</P>
<P>
"These contracts would therefore have to be renegotiated if the
commission's initial view is ultimately confirmed," said the EU
executive branch, which is responsible for proposing and enforcing
regulations of the European Union. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
