<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0550 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Road to Peace in DRC Long, Bumpy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Crucial talks to end the
11-month-long war in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) are
still busy giving final touches to a draft ceasefire agreement in
Lusaka, Zambia, however, a quick breakthrough is still not in
sight.
</P>
<P>
The talks, which started on Monday, are attended by defense and
foreign ministers from 14 members of Southern African Development
Community, as well as Rwanda, Uganda and Libya.
</P>
<P>
The highly-expected meeting ushers in a glimmering of hope for
the restoration of peace in the vast central African country, but
the postponement of the summit reminds people that the road to
peace in the DRC is long and bumpy.
</P>
<P>
Heads of state from countries in the region are expected to
sign a ceasefire agreement at the ensuing summit and to map out
modalities for the withdrawal of foreign troops. However, their
wishes can be easily crushed by the grave differences among the
players in the armed conflict.
</P>
<P>
The war in the former Zaire, the third largest country in the
continent, has drawn in at least six African countries and
threatens to engulf the continent.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia have provided military support to
DRC President Laurent Kabila at the latter's invitation.
</P>
<P>
However, Uganda and Rwanda are supporting the rebels and
maintaining military presence in eastern part of the DRC in the
excuse of defending their borders.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan State Minister Amama Mbabazi has warned that Kampala
would not sign the documents if its security concerns were not
adequately addressed at the forthcoming summit. If Uganda did not
honor the ceasefire and refused to withdraw its troops there, it
would constitute a major obstacle to the restoration of real peace
in the DRC.
</P>
<P>
The United States, which regards Libya as its leading enemy in
Africa, would not tolerate Libya for deploying a large
peacekeeping force abroad and play a major role in the DRC peace
process. Libya initiated a ceasefire agreement of the DRC civil
war in Sirte of Libya on April 18.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials has accused Libya of attempting to use its
peacekeeping forces in the DRC to back the Ugandan rebels.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that the United States would use its
power and influence to block the participation of Libya in the
multinational peacekeeping forces to be deployed in the DRC and
would not easily accept any peacekeeping program in which Libya
plays a leading role.
</P>
<P>
The deployment of peacekeeping forces should have the nod from
the Organization of African Unity and the U.N. Security Council.
It is expected that the U.S would not give its nod when the matter
seeks approval from the world body.
</P>
<P>
What's more, the Tutsi rebels who have been trying to topple
the Kabila administration have now split into two major factions,
with one based in Goma in the east and the other in Kisangani,
northern DRC, due to what is said as nearly insurmountable
strategic and tactic differences. The Congolese Liberation
Movement which is fighting government troops in the northern part
of the country is now another rebel force.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from all these three rebel groups are now in
Lusaka and they all demand to sign the pact on behalf of the rebel
forces. Analysts here predict that an inevitable rebel clash would
precede the signing of the accord. The disparities among the
different rebel groups would add to the difficulty in the
realization of peace in the third largest African country.
</P>
<P>
Although Kabila has agreed to talk directly with the rebels,
this has never been a reality up to now. The rebel forces have
warned more than once that they would not sign the pact if Kabila
refused to hold direct talks with them.
</P>
<P>
The ministers are still bargaining over the details of the
accord and trying to iron out their differences, but how to solve
all the problems mentioned above would matter much to the peace
process. The torch of hope is flickering there and is real, but it
looks somewhat distant. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0551 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNCHR Envoy Calls for Halt to Attacks Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Special Envoy Dennis McNamara of
U.N.High Commissioner for Refugees Wednesday called on the
returned refugees in Kosovo to stop attacks against the Serb and
Gypsy population in Kosovo, the Albanian Telegraphic Agency (ATA)
said.
</P>
