<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Government Approves Four-year Economic Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Italian government Wednesday evening
approved the four-year economic plan, entailing a lighter budget for
next year than originally expected with no mention of highly
controversial pension cuts.
</P>
<P>
The 2000 budget was put at 15 trillion lire (8 billion U.S.
dollars), comprising 11.5 trillion lire in cuts, with the ax falling
heavily on the public employment sector and regional health spending,
and 3.5 trillion lire in spending designed to boost growth.
</P>
<P>
The 2001 budget was also put at 15 trillion lire, with 7.5 trillion
lire going towards boosting growth, while the budgets for the
following two years were put at 11.5 trillion lire.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema said at a press conference
later that the government did not intend to reduce welfare spending
but rather reform the system to iron out imbalances, stressing that
this would be done through negotiations with unions and management.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema put the emphasis on job creation and growth Wednesday
night, saying that the money set aside for investment should create
thousands of jobs and complaining that attention had focused over the
last week on "issues of secondary importance."
</P>
<P>
"The plan's primary objective is to establish the economic
foundations for encouraging growth and employment, this represents the
great challenge," he said, adding that talks with unions and
management on the details of these policies would follow.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to allay concerns that the lighter line of the 2000
budget risked compromising Italy's ability to meet its euro-zone
commitments as laid down in the Stability Pact, D'Alema said that
"Italy is not at the bottom of the class when it comes to its public
accounts."
</P>
<P>
Italian Treasury ministry undersecretary Piero Giarda said that the
11.5 trillion lire in cuts were designed to ensure that Italy hit a
deficit-to-GDP ratio of 1.5 percent next year, as required by the
Stability Pact.
</P>
<P>
Amato is due to go through the contents of the plan with European
Union finance ministers on July 12.
</P>
<P>
The plan forecasts growth of 1.3 percent in 1999 and 2.2 percent in
2000, putting it at the bottom end of the EU economic table, although
a small sign of encouragement was given by better-than- expected first
quarter growth figures released this morning.
</P>
<P>
The plan also aims to make public debt to fall to 99.6 percent of
GDP by 2003, while the inflation rate is expected to drop to 1.2
percent next year, 1.1 percent in 2001, remaining stable at 1 percent
for the following two years.
</P>
<P>
On fiscal issues, the plan confirmed the goal of cutting income tax
from 27 percent to 26 percent as well as tax breaks for poor families
and an increase in petrol tax to boost revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
