<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0573 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hill Set for Silverstone Swansong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Englishman Damon Hill stunned the
motor racing world by revealing he will race for the final time at
the British Grand Prix on July 11.
</P>
<P>
The former world champion guaranteed himself an emotional and
lucrative send-off in front of 100,000 fans by completing an
astonishing U-turn when all in Formula One expected him to quit
now.
</P>
<P>
Hill made his decision after three days of discussions with his
family and friends at his Spanish villa. The 38-year-old will be
at Silverstone on Thursday for a two-day test in his Jordan car
ahead of the race at the Northamptonshire circuit.
</P>
<P>
"I am delighted to give Damon this opportunity in front of the
sponsors and fans who have supported his great career," said team
chief Eddie Jordan. "I hope everyone will join us in making this a
triumphant send-off."
</P>
<P>
The Dublin-based driver had flown in from Spain for a head-to-
head with Jordan to apparently thrash out the final severance
details of his contract. But after a day of increasing speculation
the team announced that Hill had told them he would drive his last
grand prix at Silverstone.
</P>
<P>
The sponsors of both Hill and his team would have been keen to
have their main drawing card present for the most important race
the calendar.
</P>
<P>
The British Grand Prix is also a huge pay-day for Hill whose
merchandise sales at the track are greater than the rest of the
drivers combined.
</P>
<P>
Hill's 5 million pound salary with the Silverstone-based outfit
is also understood to have been a sticking point. Half of that
salary has already been paid with next week's race marking the mid-
way point of the season.
</P>
<P>
Hill would then have been due the next installment for the
remainder of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
The Briton has given no reason for his decision, which is a
massive change of heart given his emotional state after he was
forced to retire from last week's French Grand Prix in Magny-Cours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
