<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0586 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Becker Ends Wimbledon Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Three-time Wimbledon champion Boris
Becker of Germany ended his career on the All England Club lawn
tennis courts when he lost to second seed Patrick Rafter of
Australia 6-3, 6-2, 6-3 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Becker, 31 but still the youngest men's champion in Wimbledon
history, was outplayed by the Australian on Wednesday as the serve
that struck a thousand aces on the grass of the All-England Club
lost its bite.
</P>
<P>
The German, champion in 1985, 1986 and 1989, bowed out with a
wave and a smile, and the fans cheered him to the roof tops.
</P>
<P>
"It was a nice way to say good-bye," said Becker, smiling. "
This place was always special to me, it made me who I am today.
It gave me all the possibilities, all the freedom to do what I
want to do with my life from now one and I'm very thankful."
</P>
<P>
"I have so many memories, so many things have happened. I'm
thankful I had the chance to come back and play some decent tennis.
"
</P>
<P>
Rafter had no time for sentiment, saying he hadn't felt bad
about beating the Wimbledon legend. "He's obviously a presence
here but his game wasn't firing today."
</P>
<P>
The Australian plays eighth seed Todd Martin who eased past
last year's finalist Goran Ivanisevic 7-6, 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Ivanisevic, a three-time finalist here but never a winner, was
devastated by his loss.
</P>
<P>
"I was pretty slow and didn't return well. Every volley I was
panicking when I tried to hit it. I just had a bad day and when
you have a bad day, it's bad luck," said the 10th seed.
</P>
<P>
France's Cedric Pioline, losing finalist in 1997, beat Karol
Kucera of Slovakia, the 13th seed, 6-4, 5-7, 7-6, 4-6, 6-3 and
will play Henman.
</P>
<P>
American Andre Agassi and Gustavo Kuerten of Brazil, who have
both won the French Open, meet in the other quarter-final after
finding enough time amid the showers to win on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Pete Sampras, yet to drop his serve or a set,
continued his cruise towards a sixth final in seven years when he
beat Daniel Nestor of Canada 6-3, 6-4, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
"I had four days off since I last played, and it definitely
affects your rhythm," the defending champion said.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's play was washed out and Sampras's match was a victim
of the early finish on Monday, caused by showers.
</P>
<P>
Sixth seed Tim Henman delighted home fans when he saved three
match points on the way to beating former world number one Jim
Courier 4-6, 7-5, 7-5, 6-7, 9-7 in a match lasting four hours 30
minutes and spread over three days.
</P>
<P>
Sampras meets seventh seed Mark Philippoussis of Australia who
beat another Briton Greg Rusedski 2-6, 7-6, 6-3, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
Rusedski was in control until the second set tiebreak when the
huge Australian's feared serve finally began to click and he won
it 7-6, the first set he had ever taken off the ninth seed.
</P>
<P>
From then on the Briton lost heart and by the fourth set
Philippoussis was breaking the fastest serve in men's tennis with
embarrassing ease.
</P>
<P>
Second women's seed Steffi Graf showed no mercy when she
finished off Belgium's teenage qualifier Kim Clijsters in eight
minutes to win their rain-delayed match 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Graf plays sixth seed Venus Williams in the quarter-finals
following the powerful American's 3-6, 6-3, 6-2 win over Russian
Anna Kournikova.
</P>
<P>
A woman qualifier will reach the semifinals at Wimbledon for
the first time after American Alexandra Stevenson came from a set
and a matchpoint down to beat Lisa Raymond 2-6, 7-6, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old now plays Jelena Dokic, the 16-year-old
Australian who beat top seed Martina Hingis in the first round.
The last qualifier to reach the Wimbledon semifinals was John
McEnroe in 1977.
</P>
<P>
Stevenson, at the centre of a row over racism after reported
comments by her mother, read a statement at her press conference
saying her mother had been misquoted by British newspapers.
</P>
<P>
But she confirmed she had been called a "nigger" during the pre-
Wimbledon Roehampton tournament in 1998. She said she was
delighted that she and Williams were both in the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
"It means a great deal to me. I represent both African-American
and Caucasian - without race or anything I think it's great
because we're both friends," said Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
Williams won just four points in the first four games as
Kournikova streaked into a 4-0 lead. But the American began to
find her length in the second set and eventually won with ease.
</P>
<P>
Mirjana Lucic, the unseeded Croatian who knocked out fourth
seed Monica Seles in the previous round, ground down Thailand's
Tamarine Tanasugarn 7-5 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Lucic, 17, now meets last year's losing finalist Nathalie
Tauziat of France, the eighth seed, who beat the 15th seed
Dominique Van Roost of Belgium 6-3, 3-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Lindsay Davenport of the U.S., the second seed, will play
defending champion Jana Novotna in the other women's quarter-final
after they both won on Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
