<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Factfile on Boris Becker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- Following are facts and figures on
Boris Becker who played his last match at Wimbledon on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Born - November 22 1967 in Leimen, Germany
</P>
<P>
Height 1.90 m, weight 85 kg
</P>
<P>
Righthanded player
</P>
<P>
Current singles ATP ranking: 89
</P>
<P>
Best career ranking: 1 (January 1991)
</P>
<P>
Becker has made more than 24 million U.S. dollars in a 16-year
career.
</P>
<P>
He has 49 singles titles and 15 doubles titles.
</P>
<P>
Grand Slam record: Six singles titles. Australian Open 1991 and
1996. Wimbledon 1985, 1986 and 1989. U.S. Open 1989. Wimbledon
runner-up 1988, 1990, 1991 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Becker was the youngest Wimbledon men's champion in 1985 at the
age of 17 years seven months. He is also the only unseeded player
to win and was the first German champion.
</P>
<P>
He won his last Grand Slam tournament in Australia in 1996 but
at Wimbledon later in the year he ruptured a tendon in his wrist
and has had problems on and off with injury ever since.
</P>
<P>
At the 1997 Wimbledon he lost in four sets to Pete Sampras in
the quarter-finals and announced his retirement from major
tournaments. He lost finals to Sampras in 1995, to Michael Stich
in 1991 and Stefan Edberg in 1988 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
After missing the 1998 tournament he returned for a final
farewell this year and was knocked out by second seed Pat Rafter
of Australia in the fourth round. He plans to retire from the game
in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
He has a classic serve and volley game suited to grass and fast
surfaces and was never happy on clay. His best result at the
French Open was reaching the semifinals twice.
</P>
<P>
He was nicknamed Boom Boom for his big serve and loved by
crowds for his acrobatics on court, leaping to reach volleys and
rolling on the court.
</P>
<P>
A member of German Davis Cup team for many years, Becker
piloted his country to victory in 1988 and 1989. Retired from team
in April but remains team manager.
</P>
<P>
Won Olympic doubles title in 1992 with Michael Stich.
</P>
<P>
Married Barbara Feltus in December 1993. Son Noah was born in
January 1994. Expecting second child in August.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
