<HEADLINE> China, Russia Have to Take a Grueling Travel Schedule </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese and Russian teams
have been complaining about a grueling travel shedule, claiming
the scheduling of the tournament favored the United States.
</P>
<P>
If China makes it to the final, the team will have traveled 12,
673 miles and weathered four cross-country trips.
</P>
<P>
"It is the cruelest schedule we have ever experienced, " said
Ma Yuanan, Chinese head coach. "It is very, very tough. The first
two cross-country trips have cost us a lot and our players are
feeling very tired."
</P>
<P>
China is in Group D with Sweden, and faces Russia in the
quarterfinal tonight in San Jose. If China go through to the
semifinal, they'll have to fly back to Boston tomorrow for the
game on June 4.
</P>
<P>
If they make it through the final, another cross-country trip
will be required. The final is being held in the Rose Bowl in
Pasadena, California
</P>
<P>
Russia started in Foxboro, Mass., then traveled to Portland,
Ore. From there it was on to Giants Stadium in New Jersey, and
Wednesday the Russians were in San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
Norway, another favorite, will have to cover 9,471 miles and
make three cross-country trips.
</P>
<P>
The United States, by comparison, will only need to travel 5,
498 miles and made only one cross-country trip. That is for the
final on June 10.
</P>
<P>
Organizing committee president Marla Messing said the Women's
World Cup had met FIFA demands about the travel requirements "to
the extent feasible."
</P>
<P>
"I think on the whole, in the context of the event taking place
in the United States, the travel schedule is fair," she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
