<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers End Protest After Agreement With Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, June 30 (Xinhua) -- The farmers in Croatia ended their
five-day protest on Wednesday after the government agreed to
protect the farmers' interests, local TV reported.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement reached between the two sides, the
Croatian government and the farmers union will design a formula to
protect the domestic agricultural production in keeping with the
principles of the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also establish a mixed committee to oversee
the issue of state debts owed to farmers.
</P>
<P>
The price of the wheat will be more rational and will be more
than one kuna per kilogram this year, said the report.
</P>
<P>
After the agreement was reached, the farmers' union announced
that the farmers will stop their protest and all the road blocks
will be removed within eight hours.
</P>
<P>
As many as 12,000-15,000 farmers, who started their protests
last Saturday, blocked the roads with tractors and trucks in seven
of 21 prefectures to press for a dialogue with the government.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that the government ban the import of
agricultural products until surplus domestic products are
purchased. Besides they demanded that government pay back the
money owned to them and raise the wheat price from 1.1 kuna to 1.
32 kuna per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the farmers' union held a talk with the government,
but the two sides failed to reach an agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990701.0613 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Industrial Zones Play Important Role in Vietnamese Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 1 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's industrial zones (IZs) and
export processing zones (EPZs) produced goods worth a total of 1.2
billion U.S. dollars in the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented 20 percent of the nation's industrial
output, English daily Vietnam News Thursday quoted Vietnam's
national management board for IZs and EPZs as saying.
</P>
<P>
These zones achieved a combined export value of 800 million
U.S. dollars, 16 percent of the national total export value.
</P>
<P>
There are 66 IZs, EPZs and high technology zones in 27
Vietnamese provinces and cities, of which 13 are in the north
Vietnam, 13 in the central region and the remainder in the south
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, 76 projects capitalized at a
total of more than 300 million U.S. dollars have been licensed to
operate in these zones. Of these, 36 are foreign-invested with
capital totaling 236 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
This has brought the total number of operational projects in
Vietnam's IZs and EPZs to 732 with a combined investment of 6.8
billion U.S. dollars. More than 40 percent of these projects'
registered capital has been disbursed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
